33
00:05:52,520 --> 00:05:54,788
 <i>(applause quiets)</i> 

34
00:05:54,822 --> 00:05:57,224
ADAM GOPNIK: <i>If you're here,</i>
 <i>then you already know</i> 

35
00:05:57,257 --> 00:05:59,627
 <i>who she is, and that is one</i>
 <i>of the most important</i> 

36
00:05:59,660 --> 00:06:01,995
 <i>musical figures of our time.</i> 

37
00:06:02,029 --> 00:06:03,931
 <i>Lydia Tár is many things:</i> 

38
00:06:03,964 --> 00:06:07,334
 <i>a piano performance graduate</i>
 <i>at the Curtis Institute,</i> 

39
00:06:07,367 --> 00:06:09,837
 <i>Phi Beta Kappa from Harvard.</i> 

40
00:06:09,870 --> 00:06:14,207
 <i>She got her PhD in Musicology</i>
 <i>from the University of Vienna,</i> 

41
00:06:14,241 --> 00:06:16,644
 <i>specializing in</i>
 <i>the indigenous music</i> 

42
00:06:16,677 --> 00:06:19,813
 <i>of the Ucayali Valley</i>
 <i>in Eastern Peru,</i> 

43
00:06:19,847 --> 00:06:21,815
 <i>where she spent five years</i> 

44
00:06:21,849 --> 00:06:23,651
 <i>among the Shipibo-Konibo people.</i> 

45
00:06:23,684 --> 00:06:27,287
 <i>As a conductor,</i>
 <i>Tár began her career</i> 

46
00:06:27,320 --> 00:06:28,656
 <i>with the Cleveland Orchestra,</i> 

47
00:06:28,689 --> 00:06:30,458
 <i>one of the so-called</i>
 <i>"Big Five."</i> 

48
00:06:30,491 --> 00:06:32,560
 <i>A string of</i>
 <i>important posts followed,</i> 

49
00:06:32,593 --> 00:06:35,195
 <i>including</i>
 <i>the Philadelphia Orchestra,</i> 

50
00:06:35,228 --> 00:06:36,430
 <i>the Chicago Symphony Orchestra,</i> 

51
00:06:36,464 --> 00:06:37,931
 <i>the Boston Symphony Orchestra,</i> 

52
00:06:37,965 --> 00:06:39,667
 <i>until she at last arrived here</i> 

53
00:06:39,700 --> 00:06:42,936
 <i>at our own</i>
 <i>New York Philharmonic.</i> 

54
00:06:42,970 --> 00:06:44,472
 <i>With the latter, she organized</i> 

55
00:06:44,505 --> 00:06:46,874
 <i>the Highway 10</i>
 <i>refugee concerts in Zaatari,</i> 

56
00:06:46,907 --> 00:06:51,445
 <i>which were attended</i>
 <i>by over 75,000 people.</i> 

57
00:06:51,479 --> 00:06:53,080
 <i>She's become particularly</i>
 <i>well-known</i> 

58
00:06:53,113 --> 00:06:54,715
 <i>for commissioning</i>
 <i>contemporary work</i> 

59
00:06:54,748 --> 00:06:58,151
 <i>from, among others,</i>
 <i>Jennifer Higdon, Caroline Shaw,</i> 

60
00:06:58,185 --> 00:07:00,588
 <i>Julia Wolfe</i>
 <i>and Hildur Gudnadóttir.</i> 

61
00:07:00,621 --> 00:07:03,624
 <i>And she's made a point</i>
 <i>of programming their works</i> 

62
00:07:03,657 --> 00:07:06,827
 <i>alongside composers</i>
 <i>of the canon.</i> 

63
00:07:06,860 --> 00:07:08,328
 <i>She's been quoted as saying,</i> 

64
00:07:08,361 --> 00:07:11,098
 <i>"These composers</i>
 <i>are having a conversation</i> 

65
00:07:11,131 --> 00:07:13,934
 <i>and it may not always</i>
 <i>be so polite."</i> 

66
00:07:13,967 --> 00:07:16,737
 <i>Lydia Tár has also written</i>
 <i>music for the stage and screen.</i> 

67
00:07:16,770 --> 00:07:21,509
 <i>She is in fact one of only 15</i>
 <i>so-called EGOTs, meaning those</i> 

68
00:07:21,542 --> 00:07:25,579
 <i>who have won all four</i>
 <i>major entertainment awards:</i> 

69
00:07:25,613 --> 00:07:29,282
 <i>an Emmy, a Grammy,</i>
 <i>an Oscar and a Tony.</i> 

70
00:07:29,316 --> 00:07:30,851
 <i>It is, as you can imagine,</i> 

71
00:07:30,884 --> 00:07:33,521
 <i>an extremely short</i>
 <i>and shimmering list</i> 

72
00:07:33,554 --> 00:07:36,690
 <i>that includes Richard Rodgers,</i>
 <i>Audrey Hepburn,</i> 

73
00:07:36,724 --> 00:07:40,360
 <i>Andrew Lloyd Webber</i>
 <i>and, of course, Mel Brooks.</i> 

74
00:07:40,393 --> 00:07:43,296
 <i>(audience laughing)</i> 

75
00:07:44,431 --> 00:07:47,601
GOPNIK: In 2010, with
the support of Eliot Kaplan,

76
00:07:47,635 --> 00:07:50,771
she founded the Accordion
Conducting Fellowship,

77
00:07:50,804 --> 00:07:53,674
which fosters entrepreneurship
and performance opportunities

78
00:07:53,707 --> 00:07:57,044
for female conductors,
allowing them residencies

79
00:07:57,077 --> 00:07:59,780
with major orchestras
around the world.

80
00:07:59,813 --> 00:08:05,118
In 2013, Berlin elected Tár
as its principal conductor,

81
00:08:05,152 --> 00:08:07,521
in succession to Andris Davis,

82
00:08:07,555 --> 00:08:10,457
and she's remained there
ever since.

83
00:08:10,490 --> 00:08:12,526
Like her mentor,
Leonard Bernstein,

84
00:08:12,560 --> 00:08:15,495
Tár has a particular
affinity for Mahler,

85
00:08:15,529 --> 00:08:17,831
whose nine symphonies
she recorded

86
00:08:17,865 --> 00:08:19,900
during her Big Five stints.

87
00:08:20,701 --> 00:08:22,636
However, she never managed
to complete

88
00:08:22,670 --> 00:08:26,173
the so-called "cycle" with
a single orchestra until now.

89
00:08:26,206 --> 00:08:27,608
Under her direction,

90
00:08:27,641 --> 00:08:29,643
Berlin has recorded eight
of the Mahler symphonies,

91
00:08:29,677 --> 00:08:32,512
saving the big one,
Symphony No. 5, for last.

92
00:08:32,546 --> 00:08:34,782
Due to the pandemic,
that performance,

93
00:08:34,815 --> 00:08:37,350
which was scheduled for
last year, had to be canceled.

94
00:08:37,384 --> 00:08:39,352
But I'm told that next month,

95
00:08:39,386 --> 00:08:42,055
she'll make a live recording
of Mahler's Fifth,

96
00:08:42,089 --> 00:08:43,724
which will complete the cycle

97
00:08:43,757 --> 00:08:47,360
and will be issued in a box set
by Deutsche Grammophon

98
00:08:47,394 --> 00:08:49,529
just in time
for Mahler's birthday.

99
00:08:49,563 --> 00:08:53,433
As if that's not enough,
her new book, <i>Tár on Tár,</i> 

100
00:08:53,466 --> 00:08:56,970
will be published by Nan
Talese's imprint at Doubleday,

101
00:08:57,004 --> 00:09:00,407
just in time for Christmas,
a perfect stocking stuffer,

102
00:09:00,440 --> 00:09:02,810
especially if you have
a very large stocking.

103
00:09:02,843 --> 00:09:04,344
(audience laughing)

104
00:09:04,377 --> 00:09:05,779
All of us at <i>The New Yorker</i>
welcome you.

105
00:09:05,813 --> 00:09:07,848
Thank you for joining us,
Maestro, today.

106
00:09:07,881 --> 00:09:09,482
Thank you, Adam. Thank you.

107
00:09:09,516 --> 00:09:12,152
-(applause)
-Thank you.

108
00:09:13,320 --> 00:09:15,488
Lydia, I couldn't...

109
00:09:15,522 --> 00:09:18,859
I couldn't help but see you
flinch just a little bit

110
00:09:18,892 --> 00:09:20,493
as I was reading your bio.

111
00:09:20,527 --> 00:09:22,562
Was it because I forgot
some other amazing achievement?

112
00:09:22,596 --> 00:09:25,065
Or do you have
a slight self-consciousness

113
00:09:25,098 --> 00:09:27,234
about the incredibly
varied things

114
00:09:27,267 --> 00:09:29,102
that you've accomplished?

115
00:09:29,136 --> 00:09:34,441
Well, in today's world,
"varied," it-it's a dirty word.

116
00:09:34,474 --> 00:09:36,543
I mean,
our era is one of specialists,

117
00:09:36,576 --> 00:09:39,479
and if you're trying to do
more than one thing,

118
00:09:39,512 --> 00:09:41,248
it's, you know,
it's often frowned upon.

119
00:09:41,281 --> 00:09:42,850
Every artist gets typecast.

120
00:09:42,883 --> 00:09:44,384
Oh, yes. Aggressively so.

121
00:09:44,417 --> 00:09:46,119
Well, do you think there'll be
a moment, though,

122
00:09:46,153 --> 00:09:48,321
when the classical music
community,

123
00:09:48,355 --> 00:09:51,792
uh, decides not to use
sexual distinctions

124
00:09:51,825 --> 00:09:53,761
to differentiate artists?

125
00:09:53,794 --> 00:09:56,163
I'm probably
the wrong person to ask

126
00:09:56,196 --> 00:09:58,398
since I don't, uh,
read reviews.

127
00:09:58,431 --> 00:10:00,000
-Never, really?
-No.

128
00:10:00,033 --> 00:10:04,404
But it is odd, I-I think,
that anyone ever felt compelled

129
00:10:04,437 --> 00:10:07,374
to substitute
"maestro" with "maestra."

130
00:10:07,407 --> 00:10:10,711
I mean, we don't call women
astronauts "astronettes."

131
00:10:10,744 --> 00:10:12,479
-GOPNIK: Mm-hmm. Right.
-(audience chuckling)

132
00:10:12,512 --> 00:10:16,249
But as to the question
of, uh, gender bias,

133
00:10:16,283 --> 00:10:18,819
I really have nothing
to complain about.

134
00:10:18,852 --> 00:10:21,789
Nor, for that matter, should
Marin Alsop, JoAnn Falletta,

135
00:10:21,822 --> 00:10:24,257
uh, Laurence Equilbey
and Nathalie Stutzmann.

136
00:10:24,291 --> 00:10:26,994
I mean, there's so many
incredible women

137
00:10:27,027 --> 00:10:28,461
who came before us.

138
00:10:28,495 --> 00:10:30,931
You know, women who did
the-the real lifting.

139
00:10:30,964 --> 00:10:32,132
That-that's fascinating.

140
00:10:32,165 --> 00:10:34,101
Can you... Who, for instance?

141
00:10:34,134 --> 00:10:35,402
Uh, okay, sure.

142
00:10:35,435 --> 00:10:37,604
Uh, first and foremost,
Nadia Boulanger.

143
00:10:37,637 --> 00:10:40,573
I mean, that would be
the, uh, happy example.

144
00:10:40,607 --> 00:10:43,777
Uh, the sad one would be
Antonia Brico,

145
00:10:43,811 --> 00:10:46,747
who by all accounts
was an incredible conductor

146
00:10:46,780 --> 00:10:50,117
but was ghettoized
into the nonglamorous status

147
00:10:50,150 --> 00:10:52,185
of a "guest conductor"

148
00:10:52,219 --> 00:10:55,088
and essentially
treated as a dog act.

149
00:10:55,122 --> 00:10:57,290
A dog...
Uh, she never got the chance

150
00:10:57,324 --> 00:10:58,525
to lead a major orchestra?

151
00:10:58,558 --> 00:11:00,593
Well, yes.
Yes, she did, uh, conduct

152
00:11:00,627 --> 00:11:02,763
the, uh, Berlin Philharmonic,
as well as the Met,

153
00:11:02,796 --> 00:11:05,966
but, again,
only as a guest conductor.

154
00:11:05,999 --> 00:11:08,001
You know, at, I mean,
at that time it was...

155
00:11:08,035 --> 00:11:10,303
it was all gender spectacle.

156
00:11:10,337 --> 00:11:11,739
But fortunately, times change,

157
00:11:11,772 --> 00:11:13,707
and-and the Pauline
conversion is...

158
00:11:13,741 --> 00:11:15,475
-(chuckling): "Pauline..."
-... if not complete,

159
00:11:15,508 --> 00:11:16,977
then it's-it's evolving nicely.

160
00:11:17,010 --> 00:11:19,646
N-No less, um,
having fallen off its horse.

161
00:11:19,679 --> 00:11:22,149
Um, Lydia, could we talk
a little bit

162
00:11:22,182 --> 00:11:24,284
-about, uh, translation?
-Mm-hmm.

163
00:11:24,317 --> 00:11:25,919
'Cause I think
there's still people

164
00:11:25,953 --> 00:11:29,289
who think of the conductor
as a kind of human metronome.

165
00:11:30,423 --> 00:11:33,326
Well, yeah,
that's-that's partly true.

166
00:11:33,360 --> 00:11:35,128
-Yeah, but it's...
-But keeping time,

167
00:11:35,162 --> 00:11:36,730
it's-it's no small thing.

168
00:11:36,764 --> 00:11:38,732
But I suspect there's
a lot more to it than that.

169
00:11:38,766 --> 00:11:40,433
Yeah, well,
I-I would hope so, yes.

170
00:11:40,467 --> 00:11:43,003
-But time is the thing.
-Uh-huh.

171
00:11:43,036 --> 00:11:47,440
Time is-is the essential piece
of, uh, interpretation.

172
00:11:47,474 --> 00:11:49,209
You cannot start without me.

173
00:11:49,242 --> 00:11:51,278
See, I start the clock.

174
00:11:51,311 --> 00:11:54,748
Now, my left hand shapes,
but my right hand,

175
00:11:54,782 --> 00:11:59,019
the second hand, marks time
and moves it forward.

176
00:11:59,052 --> 00:12:03,090
However, unlike a clock,
sometimes my second hand stops,

177
00:12:03,123 --> 00:12:06,226
which means that time stops.

178
00:12:06,259 --> 00:12:09,396
Now, the illusion is that,
like you,

179
00:12:09,429 --> 00:12:11,664
I'm responding to
the orchestra in real time...

180
00:12:11,698 --> 00:12:13,700
-Right, right. -... making the
decision about the right moment

181
00:12:13,733 --> 00:12:15,402
to restart the thing,
or reset it,

182
00:12:15,435 --> 00:12:18,005
or throw time out
the window altogether.

183
00:12:18,038 --> 00:12:21,441
The reality is that right
from the very beginning,

184
00:12:21,474 --> 00:12:23,543
I know precisely
what time it is...

185
00:12:23,576 --> 00:12:25,278
-Really? That's...
-... and the exact moment

186
00:12:25,312 --> 00:12:28,481
that you and I will arrive
at our destination together.

187
00:12:28,515 --> 00:12:32,119
You know, the only real,
uh, discovery for me

188
00:12:32,152 --> 00:12:33,854
is in rehearsal.

189
00:12:33,887 --> 00:12:35,956
It's never,
never in performance.

190
00:12:35,989 --> 00:12:39,793
Hard question, I know, but
if you could define one thing

191
00:12:39,827 --> 00:12:42,863
that Bernstein gave you,
what would it be?

192
00:12:44,631 --> 00:12:46,233
Kavvanah.

193
00:12:46,266 --> 00:12:47,567
Yeah, it's-it's the Hebrew word

194
00:12:47,600 --> 00:12:50,503
for attention to meaning
or-or intent.

195
00:12:50,537 --> 00:12:52,172
You know, what are
the composer's priorities,

196
00:12:52,205 --> 00:12:54,607
and what are yours, and how do
they complement one another?

197
00:12:54,641 --> 00:12:56,609
Right, kavvanah. I think
that's a word that will have

198
00:12:56,643 --> 00:12:58,846
a slightly different meaning
for many in our audience.

199
00:12:58,879 --> 00:13:01,915
-Well, yes, yes, I imagine so.
-(audience murmuring)

200
00:13:01,949 --> 00:13:03,550
Am I right in thinking
that a conductor

201
00:13:03,583 --> 00:13:06,286
was not always, uh,
an onstage presence

202
00:13:06,319 --> 00:13:07,754
-in classical music?
-No, that's right.

203
00:13:07,787 --> 00:13:09,789
I-I think I read someplace
that it actually was

204
00:13:09,823 --> 00:13:11,892
the first violin, for a long
time, who was responsible.

205
00:13:11,925 --> 00:13:14,494
Yes, the first violinist,
whether they had any interest

206
00:13:14,527 --> 00:13:16,129
or-or skill in it or not.

207
00:13:16,163 --> 00:13:18,932
Wh-When did that change,
and-and who changed it?

208
00:13:18,966 --> 00:13:22,102
With the French composer,
Jean-Baptiste Lully,

209
00:13:22,135 --> 00:13:26,106
who reportedly, uh,
used a, uh, rather enormous,

210
00:13:26,139 --> 00:13:30,343
rather pointy staff to pound
the tempi into the floor.

211
00:13:30,377 --> 00:13:31,611
It's not something I imagine

212
00:13:31,644 --> 00:13:34,081
the players particularly,
uh, appreciated.

213
00:13:34,114 --> 00:13:37,951
Uh, anyway, uh, that technique
ended during a performance

214
00:13:37,985 --> 00:13:39,953
when Lully accidentally

215
00:13:39,987 --> 00:13:42,155
stabbed himself in the foot
with the thing and died.

216
00:13:42,189 --> 00:13:45,158
-(audience laughter)
-Yeah, of-of-of gangrene.

217
00:13:45,192 --> 00:13:47,060
But anyway...

218
00:13:47,094 --> 00:13:49,930
-(applause)
-Yeah.

219
00:13:49,963 --> 00:13:53,133
Anyway, but the conductor

220
00:13:53,166 --> 00:13:56,904
really becomes essential
as the ensembles get bigger.

221
00:13:56,937 --> 00:13:59,639
And once again,
we go back to Beethoven.

222
00:13:59,672 --> 00:14:02,575
* Buh, buh, buh, bum,
buh, buh, buh, bum. *

223
00:14:02,609 --> 00:14:04,777
Now, that doesn't start
with the eighth note.

224
00:14:04,811 --> 00:14:07,314
The downbeat--
* Buh, buh, buh --

225
00:14:07,347 --> 00:14:08,916
it's silent, right?

226
00:14:08,949 --> 00:14:11,618
So someone had to start
that clock.

227
00:14:11,651 --> 00:14:14,621
Someone had to, uh,
plant their flag in the sand

228
00:14:14,654 --> 00:14:17,090
and say, "Follow me," you know?

229
00:14:17,124 --> 00:14:20,660
And when that someone was
Lenny, the orchestra was led

230
00:14:20,693 --> 00:14:24,864
on the most extraordinary
tour of pleasures.

231
00:14:24,898 --> 00:14:27,767
'Cause he knew the music,
Mahler especially,

232
00:14:27,800 --> 00:14:29,903
as well or better than anyone.

233
00:14:29,937 --> 00:14:33,406
And he would often play
with the form.

234
00:14:33,440 --> 00:14:34,807
'Cause he wanted an orchestra
to feel

235
00:14:34,841 --> 00:14:36,876
that they had never seen,
let alone heard

236
00:14:36,910 --> 00:14:39,879
or-or performed
any of that music.

237
00:14:39,913 --> 00:14:42,115
So he-he would do
radical things,

238
00:14:42,149 --> 00:14:44,584
like, uh, disregarding
the tempo primo

239
00:14:44,617 --> 00:14:46,954
or-or ending this phrase
molto ritardando,

240
00:14:46,987 --> 00:14:49,589
even though
it had no such marking.

241
00:14:49,622 --> 00:14:51,124
Was he over-egging it?

242
00:14:51,158 --> 00:14:52,625
Oh, no, no, no. Not at all.

243
00:14:52,659 --> 00:14:56,429
He, he, he celebrated the joy
of his discovery.

244
00:14:56,463 --> 00:14:57,998
You just told us a moment ago

245
00:14:58,031 --> 00:15:00,467
that your discovery
takes place in rehearsal.

246
00:15:00,500 --> 00:15:03,003
When will that process
begin again for you?

247
00:15:03,770 --> 00:15:05,372
We start on Monday.

248
00:15:05,405 --> 00:15:07,340
-Immediately?
-Mm.

249
00:15:07,374 --> 00:15:09,776
With this one,
it really is about

250
00:15:09,809 --> 00:15:14,114
trying to read the tea leaves
of-of Mahler's intention.

251
00:15:14,147 --> 00:15:15,715
I mean, we know a great deal
about this

252
00:15:15,748 --> 00:15:17,417
with his other symphonies.

253
00:15:17,450 --> 00:15:19,852
You know, he was so inspired
by the poetry of Rückert

254
00:15:19,886 --> 00:15:22,055
that for years he didn't set
another author to music.

255
00:15:22,089 --> 00:15:25,258
But all of this changes
with the Five.

256
00:15:25,292 --> 00:15:27,560
The Five is a mystery.

257
00:15:27,594 --> 00:15:30,163
And the only clue he leaves us

258
00:15:30,197 --> 00:15:32,199
is on the cover
of the manuscript itself.

259
00:15:32,232 --> 00:15:36,469
Yes, the-the dedication
to his new wife, Alma.

260
00:15:36,503 --> 00:15:38,471
So if you're gonna partner
with Mahler

261
00:15:38,505 --> 00:15:41,274
on his, uh, fifth symphony,

262
00:15:41,308 --> 00:15:42,842
the first thing you must do

263
00:15:42,875 --> 00:15:47,280
is try to understand
that very complex marriage.

264
00:15:47,314 --> 00:15:49,983
And would you say that you have
a different interpretation

265
00:15:50,017 --> 00:15:52,452
of that marriage
than Bernstein did?

266
00:15:54,054 --> 00:15:58,591
You mentioned my ethnographic
fieldwork in the Amazon.

267
00:15:58,625 --> 00:16:01,394
Well, Adam, the Shipibo-Konibo

268
00:16:01,428 --> 00:16:03,963
only receive an <i>icaro,</i> or song,

269
00:16:03,997 --> 00:16:05,898
if the singer is there, right?

270
00:16:05,932 --> 00:16:09,736
On the same side of the-the
spirit that-that created it.

271
00:16:09,769 --> 00:16:13,173
And in that way, the past
and the present converge.

272
00:16:13,206 --> 00:16:16,843
It's the flip sides
of the same cosmic coin.

273
00:16:16,876 --> 00:16:19,879
That definition of fidelity
makes sense to me.

274
00:16:19,912 --> 00:16:22,215
But Lenny,
he believed in <i>teshuvah.</i> 

275
00:16:22,249 --> 00:16:24,817
The Talmudic power
to reach back into time

276
00:16:24,851 --> 00:16:27,620
and-and transform
the, uh, significance

277
00:16:27,654 --> 00:16:29,322
of one's past deeds.

278
00:16:29,356 --> 00:16:33,560
So when he played the Adagietto
at Robert Kennedy's funeral,

279
00:16:33,593 --> 00:16:35,695
it ran for 12 minutes.

280
00:16:35,728 --> 00:16:38,198
-He treated it as a mass.
-(agreeing murmur)

281
00:16:38,231 --> 00:16:39,999
And, you know, if you listen
to a recording of it,

282
00:16:40,033 --> 00:16:43,803
you will no doubt feel
the tragedy and-and the pathos.

283
00:16:43,836 --> 00:16:46,439
And of course
that, uh, interpretation

284
00:16:46,473 --> 00:16:48,608
was very true for Mahler
later in life,

285
00:16:48,641 --> 00:16:50,677
after the professional bottom
dropped out

286
00:16:50,710 --> 00:16:52,779
and Alma had left him
for Gropius.

287
00:16:52,812 --> 00:16:58,017
But, as I said before,
we are dealing with time.

288
00:16:58,051 --> 00:17:02,522
And this piece was not born
into aching tragedy.

289
00:17:02,555 --> 00:17:04,857
It was born into young love.

290
00:17:04,891 --> 00:17:07,294
And so you chose...

291
00:17:07,327 --> 00:17:08,895
Love.

292
00:17:08,928 --> 00:17:11,731
-(audience murmuring)
-Right, but precisely how long?

293
00:17:11,764 --> 00:17:13,300
(quietly):
Well...

294
00:17:13,333 --> 00:17:15,402
seven minutes.

295
00:17:15,435 --> 00:17:17,670
(laughter)

296
00:17:19,206 --> 00:17:22,409
WOMAN: I was so taken
by what you said to Adam

297
00:17:22,442 --> 00:17:25,745
about, um, interpretation

298
00:17:25,778 --> 00:17:29,182
and specifically about feelings,

299
00:17:29,216 --> 00:17:31,351
and that you chose love.

300
00:17:32,252 --> 00:17:34,787
And I know it's said
that you should leave the tears

301
00:17:34,821 --> 00:17:37,056
for the audience, but...

302
00:17:37,090 --> 00:17:39,859
do you ever find yourself
overwhelmed by emotion

303
00:17:39,892 --> 00:17:41,561
when you're up there
at the podium?

304
00:17:41,594 --> 00:17:43,463
-TÁR: Yes.
-(sighs)

305
00:17:43,496 --> 00:17:45,265
Yes, that does happen.

306
00:17:45,298 --> 00:17:48,568
There's an...
an expectation-reward cycle

307
00:17:48,601 --> 00:17:50,503
with some works
and the spots in them

308
00:17:50,537 --> 00:17:53,640
that I find so incredible,
that when I'm conducting,

309
00:17:53,673 --> 00:17:56,042
it's not that
I'm rushing exactly,

310
00:17:56,075 --> 00:17:58,745
but, oh, I just can't wait
to get to that spot,

311
00:17:58,778 --> 00:18:01,214
and, yeah, it does it.
It does it every time.

312
00:18:01,248 --> 00:18:02,682
(laughs softly)

313
00:18:02,715 --> 00:18:04,751
So it's physical
as well as emotional.

314
00:18:04,784 --> 00:18:06,786
-Hmm. Hmm.
-God, it must take hours

315
00:18:06,819 --> 00:18:09,021
to come back down to earth.

316
00:18:09,055 --> 00:18:12,492
You say things after others
remember, but you won't.

317
00:18:12,525 --> 00:18:14,727
And sleep, it's impossible.

318
00:18:14,761 --> 00:18:16,663
It's like my freshman year
at Smith.

319
00:18:16,696 --> 00:18:18,598
(Tár chuckles)

320
00:18:18,631 --> 00:18:19,932
(sighs)

321
00:18:19,966 --> 00:18:21,701
Which piece does that to you?

322
00:18:21,734 --> 00:18:23,203
Oh, I saw you.

323
00:18:23,236 --> 00:18:25,672
I saw you conduct, uh,
 <i>The Rite of Spring</i> 

324
00:18:25,705 --> 00:18:27,174
at the Met last year.

325
00:18:27,207 --> 00:18:29,075
It was so powerful.

326
00:18:29,108 --> 00:18:31,244
TÁR:
Thank you. Thank you.

327
00:18:31,278 --> 00:18:34,447
It's...
It's the 11 pistol shots--

328
00:18:34,481 --> 00:18:35,848
it's a prime number--

329
00:18:35,882 --> 00:18:38,151
that strike you as both victim
and perpetrator.

330
00:18:38,185 --> 00:18:39,919
You know, it's not until
I conducted it

331
00:18:39,952 --> 00:18:43,423
that I became convinced
we're all capable of murder.

332
00:18:43,456 --> 00:18:46,226
That is a fantastic handbag,
by the way.

333
00:18:46,259 --> 00:18:48,761
Thank you.
I'm glad you like it.

334
00:18:48,795 --> 00:18:50,397
Oh, I do. I do.

335
00:18:50,430 --> 00:18:52,465
(quietly): Sorry.
Your lunch with Mr. Kaplan.

336
00:18:52,499 --> 00:18:54,234
His driver is waiting.

337
00:18:54,267 --> 00:18:55,302
All right.

338
00:18:55,335 --> 00:18:56,636
I-I'm sorry,
I've forgotten your name.

339
00:18:56,669 --> 00:18:58,205
-Whitney. Whitney Reese.
-Whitney.

340
00:18:58,238 --> 00:18:59,406
Whitney, of course.

341
00:18:59,439 --> 00:19:00,907
I'm, I'm so sorry,

342
00:19:00,940 --> 00:19:02,342
and unfortunately
I've left things a bit late

343
00:19:02,375 --> 00:19:03,743
-and there's something
I can't get out of. -Oh.

344
00:19:03,776 --> 00:19:05,144
I understand.

345
00:19:05,178 --> 00:19:07,380
Can I text you?

346
00:19:26,699 --> 00:19:28,901
It's perfect, Aldo.

347
00:19:31,338 --> 00:19:33,840
Oh. I was hoping
we could celebrate.

348
00:19:33,873 --> 00:19:36,008
No. So was I.

349
00:19:36,042 --> 00:19:37,644
I've got a class at Juilliard.

350
00:19:37,677 --> 00:19:38,811
Oh, good.

351
00:19:38,845 --> 00:19:40,480
I promised Ben.

352
00:19:40,513 --> 00:19:44,016
I'm sure you'll have a few
elbowing for an Accordion slot.

353
00:19:44,951 --> 00:19:47,720
We should open up
the fellowship.

354
00:19:47,754 --> 00:19:50,022
-What, expand our numbers?
-No, our sex.

355
00:19:50,056 --> 00:19:53,360
I mean, it feels quaint
to keep things single-gender.

356
00:19:53,393 --> 00:19:54,694
We've made our point.

357
00:19:54,727 --> 00:19:56,296
And, honestly,
we've had no real trouble

358
00:19:56,329 --> 00:19:58,431
successfully placing
any of them.

359
00:19:58,465 --> 00:20:00,333
Except one.

360
00:20:00,367 --> 00:20:01,968
Oh, well.

361
00:20:02,001 --> 00:20:04,271
She had issues.

362
00:20:04,304 --> 00:20:05,905
So I've heard.

363
00:20:05,938 --> 00:20:07,807
The topic comes up
in every Citibank meeting

364
00:20:07,840 --> 00:20:10,443
with her father.

365
00:20:10,477 --> 00:20:11,811
I'm sorry about that.

366
00:20:11,844 --> 00:20:13,079
It's fine.

367
00:20:13,112 --> 00:20:15,515
It's nothing I can't handle.

368
00:20:16,316 --> 00:20:20,787
So, you want to torpedo
Accordion's founding principle?

369
00:20:20,820 --> 00:20:22,822
We'd likely lose donors.

370
00:20:22,855 --> 00:20:25,224
Yeah, I suppose that's true.

371
00:20:25,258 --> 00:20:27,494
M-Maybe it's something
we revisit

372
00:20:27,527 --> 00:20:29,296
-down the line.
-Sure.

373
00:20:29,329 --> 00:20:31,998
Now, Bryant Park's locked
for the 25th.

374
00:20:32,031 --> 00:20:34,066
Nan asked me
to help fill the place,

375
00:20:34,100 --> 00:20:35,835
so the Kaplan Fund
is gonna buy some radio

376
00:20:35,868 --> 00:20:37,870
and outdoor advertising.

377
00:20:37,904 --> 00:20:40,006
And claqueurs.

378
00:20:40,039 --> 00:20:41,374
It's too big, Eliot.

379
00:20:41,408 --> 00:20:43,109
She should have booked
the Strand.

380
00:20:43,142 --> 00:20:44,477
Relax.

381
00:20:44,511 --> 00:20:46,679
It'll be great.

382
00:20:46,713 --> 00:20:49,081
And it almost falls
on your birthday.

383
00:20:51,050 --> 00:20:53,520
I was, uh, I was sorry
you weren't able to make it

384
00:20:53,553 --> 00:20:55,388
to my Mahler Three in London.

385
00:20:56,423 --> 00:20:58,157
Me, too.

386
00:20:59,526 --> 00:21:01,961
Uh, Petra had a school thing.

387
00:21:01,994 --> 00:21:06,399
Uh, and I promised Sharon
I'd be there.

388
00:21:07,700 --> 00:21:09,769
Of course.

389
00:21:09,802 --> 00:21:13,039
I was just hoping
for your honest opinion.

390
00:21:13,072 --> 00:21:15,908
My player rating sheets
were off the charts.

391
00:21:15,942 --> 00:21:17,877
Those are confidential, Eliot.

392
00:21:17,910 --> 00:21:20,179
Well, the principal oboist
is a big fan.

393
00:21:21,414 --> 00:21:22,582
On the way back,

394
00:21:22,615 --> 00:21:24,451
I was listening to yours
with the Israeli Phil,

395
00:21:24,484 --> 00:21:26,453
and I was struck
by what you managed to pull

396
00:21:26,486 --> 00:21:28,955
from the strings
in the last movement.

397
00:21:28,988 --> 00:21:32,559
I mean, how did you
get them there?

398
00:21:32,592 --> 00:21:33,926
Was it the hall?

399
00:21:33,960 --> 00:21:35,562
Was it the players?

400
00:21:35,595 --> 00:21:38,798
(scoffs) The players weren't
very obliging.

401
00:21:38,831 --> 00:21:40,533
The principal violinist
came up to me

402
00:21:40,567 --> 00:21:41,801
after the first rehearsal

403
00:21:41,834 --> 00:21:43,803
-and asked if I was a Jew.
-What?

404
00:21:43,836 --> 00:21:46,706
It seemed to him unusual, if
not suspicious, that a non-Jew

405
00:21:46,739 --> 00:21:50,042
would be interested
in conducting Jewish music.

406
00:21:50,076 --> 00:21:53,012
-(Eliot chuckles)
-Felt like Max Bruch.

407
00:21:53,045 --> 00:21:56,282
Well, big Jew that I am,
the Kaplan Fund has, uh,

408
00:21:56,315 --> 00:21:58,250
committed a sizable
amount to them

409
00:21:58,284 --> 00:22:00,119
-for a klezmer commission.
-Mm-hmm.

410
00:22:00,152 --> 00:22:02,121
Uh, maybe they'll invite me
to guest conduct.

411
00:22:02,154 --> 00:22:03,990
Oh, well, they'd be lucky
to have you.

412
00:22:04,023 --> 00:22:05,858
Oh, please.

413
00:22:05,892 --> 00:22:08,027
I know my place.

414
00:22:08,060 --> 00:22:10,497
Money can't always
buy you everything.

415
00:22:11,664 --> 00:22:13,700
You don't really believe that.

416
00:22:13,733 --> 00:22:16,035
I'll have you know
I tried to bribe Francesca

417
00:22:16,068 --> 00:22:17,704
to let me look at your notation.

418
00:22:17,737 --> 00:22:19,271
She sent me packing.

419
00:22:19,305 --> 00:22:20,707
Good girl.

420
00:22:21,508 --> 00:22:23,376
That gentleman sitting
over there with the gnome

421
00:22:23,410 --> 00:22:25,945
is urgently focused
on our table.

422
00:22:25,978 --> 00:22:29,181
At first, I thought
he was looking at me,

423
00:22:29,215 --> 00:22:31,283
but I think he's got
his eye on you.

424
00:22:31,317 --> 00:22:33,319
Please try and ignore him.

425
00:22:33,352 --> 00:22:35,622
I can excuse myself
and go wash my hands

426
00:22:35,655 --> 00:22:37,156
if you'd like to be alone.

427
00:22:37,189 --> 00:22:40,226
And I would never forgive you.

428
00:22:40,259 --> 00:22:42,261
The last thing I need
is to be buttonholed in here

429
00:22:42,294 --> 00:22:44,431
by someone exactly like me.

430
00:22:45,998 --> 00:22:47,767
Uh, what time are you
leaving tomorrow?

431
00:22:48,568 --> 00:22:51,103
Francesca's looking
into flights.

432
00:22:51,137 --> 00:22:52,639
Well, call her off.

433
00:22:52,672 --> 00:22:54,240
Leave when you like.

434
00:22:54,273 --> 00:22:56,242
You don't have to do that.

435
00:22:56,275 --> 00:23:00,079
My motives are not entirely
altruistic.

436
00:23:00,112 --> 00:23:02,582
Just one peek. One peek
at your performing score.

437
00:23:02,615 --> 00:23:05,351
(Tár chuckles)

438
00:23:05,384 --> 00:23:06,853
Fine.

439
00:23:06,886 --> 00:23:09,789
-Would 5:15 be okay?
-Sure.

440
00:23:09,822 --> 00:23:12,959
Okay, I mean, I do... I have
to get turned around fast.

441
00:23:12,992 --> 00:23:15,294
We're filling a vacant position.

442
00:23:15,327 --> 00:23:17,464
Oh, please tell me
it's Sebastian.

443
00:23:17,497 --> 00:23:18,798
Now, be fair, Eliot.

444
00:23:18,831 --> 00:23:21,067
Sebastian has decent technique.

445
00:23:21,100 --> 00:23:22,502
He has baton.

446
00:23:22,535 --> 00:23:24,203
A month ago,
I dropped into Bunkamura

447
00:23:24,236 --> 00:23:27,406
to watch the Turing machine
trot out Chopin One.

448
00:23:27,440 --> 00:23:30,977
Ol' Sebastian really
is Mr. Tempo Rubato.

449
00:23:31,010 --> 00:23:32,679
Robot-o is more like it.

450
00:23:32,712 --> 00:23:33,980
Why do you keep him on?

451
00:23:34,013 --> 00:23:36,348
Oh, he's Andris's man,
you know that.

452
00:23:36,382 --> 00:23:37,917
Exactly. You inherited
that decision.

453
00:23:37,950 --> 00:23:40,086
Seven years is a long time
to pretend you respect it.

454
00:23:40,119 --> 00:23:42,421
They have different
labor contracts over there.

455
00:23:44,757 --> 00:23:47,794
He's a... he's a strange guy.

456
00:23:47,827 --> 00:23:49,095
Who? Andris?

457
00:23:49,128 --> 00:23:51,097
No, Sebastian.

458
00:23:51,130 --> 00:23:53,766
He has, uh, fetishes.

459
00:23:53,800 --> 00:23:55,602
Fetishes? Like what?

460
00:23:55,635 --> 00:23:59,305
Nostalgia for prewar Kalmus
miniature scores,

461
00:23:59,338 --> 00:24:01,207
dead-stock pencils he's seen

462
00:24:01,240 --> 00:24:03,309
von Karajan hold in photographs.

463
00:24:03,342 --> 00:24:05,211
You know, that sort of thing.

464
00:24:05,244 --> 00:24:07,614
(scoffs)
That's just sad.

465
00:24:11,918 --> 00:24:14,453
Yeah, but you're not wrong.

466
00:24:14,487 --> 00:24:17,490
I am gonna have to rotate him
at some point.

467
00:24:19,759 --> 00:24:22,128
For who?

468
00:24:26,298 --> 00:24:28,067
 <i>What Love Teaches Me.</i> 

469
00:24:28,100 --> 00:24:30,336
That string notation.

470
00:24:31,771 --> 00:24:34,006
Mahler gives it to you himself.

471
00:24:36,342 --> 00:24:37,777
-Come on.
-Trust me.

472
00:24:37,810 --> 00:24:39,345
You do not want to go to school

473
00:24:39,378 --> 00:24:41,848
on someone else's
red and blue pencil.

474
00:24:41,881 --> 00:24:43,516
Least of all, mine.

475
00:24:43,550 --> 00:24:44,784
Oh, but I do.

476
00:24:44,817 --> 00:24:46,385
(sighs) All right.
Will you quit pestering me?

477
00:24:46,418 --> 00:24:48,487
Yes.

478
00:24:48,521 --> 00:24:50,489
Free bowing.

479
00:24:51,791 --> 00:24:54,393
It's not pretty
for an audience to look at,

480
00:24:54,426 --> 00:24:56,028
but if you can manage
to keep your players

481
00:24:56,062 --> 00:24:57,697
out of the weeds...

482
00:24:58,731 --> 00:25:00,733
... the sound's ferocious.

483
00:25:02,501 --> 00:25:04,436
Oh.

484
00:25:07,707 --> 00:25:10,710
There's no glory
for a robot, Eliot.

485
00:25:14,346 --> 00:25:16,549
Do your own thing.

486
00:25:18,685 --> 00:25:20,720
Hmm.

487
00:25:24,624 --> 00:25:26,392
(piano plays deep chord)

488
00:25:26,425 --> 00:25:28,661
(playing "Ró"
by Anna Thorvaldsdóttir)

489
00:25:32,164 --> 00:25:34,366
-(hollow thump)
-(soft knock)

490
00:25:36,435 --> 00:25:38,838
-(soft knock)
-(hollow thump)

491
00:25:38,871 --> 00:25:41,240
-All right, um...
-(playing stops)

492
00:25:41,273 --> 00:25:44,076
Let's... stop here.

493
00:25:44,110 --> 00:25:45,712
-Thank you, Max. Very good.
-Thanks.

494
00:25:45,745 --> 00:25:50,850
Um, just for my own
edification...

495
00:25:50,883 --> 00:25:53,052
why did you come to Juilliard?

496
00:25:53,085 --> 00:25:55,121
(Max clicks tongue)

497
00:25:56,022 --> 00:25:58,658
Uh, it's the best music
conservatory in the country?

498
00:25:58,691 --> 00:26:01,594
People from Curtis, Eastman,
and others may beg to differ.

499
00:26:01,628 --> 00:26:04,230
I mean,
Juilliard's a brand, right?

500
00:26:04,263 --> 00:26:07,066
So, did you come to study
with a brand?

501
00:26:07,099 --> 00:26:09,368
-No. -No, right.
So there's a teacher

502
00:26:09,401 --> 00:26:11,604
or graduate somewhere
down the line who, you know,

503
00:26:11,638 --> 00:26:13,305
conjured something
in your imagination.

504
00:26:13,339 --> 00:26:15,675
-Someone you aspire
to be yourself. -Mm-hmm.

505
00:26:15,708 --> 00:26:17,243
So, who was that?

506
00:26:17,276 --> 00:26:18,911
Sarah Chang.

507
00:26:18,945 --> 00:26:20,813
Hmm. So you're a violinist?

508
00:26:20,847 --> 00:26:22,348
-Yeah.
-All right, okay.

509
00:26:22,381 --> 00:26:24,216
Well, I can see why

510
00:26:24,250 --> 00:26:26,719
you would choose to conduct
a piece like this.

511
00:26:26,753 --> 00:26:29,321
Must be a familiar pleasure
in presiding over

512
00:26:29,355 --> 00:26:32,191
a bed of strings that behave
as if they're tuning.

513
00:26:32,224 --> 00:26:34,160
-(scattered laughter)
-Now...

514
00:26:34,193 --> 00:26:38,597
this piece is very au courant.

515
00:26:38,631 --> 00:26:41,300
I mean, here,
the composer tells us

516
00:26:41,333 --> 00:26:43,469
to begin with "back-and-forth
tremolo strokes

517
00:26:43,502 --> 00:26:47,506
with wire brush and slowly
sliding crotales over skin."

518
00:26:47,539 --> 00:26:50,042
Sounds like René Redzepi's
recipe for reindeer.

519
00:26:50,076 --> 00:26:51,678
(sighs heavily)

520
00:26:51,711 --> 00:26:54,280
It's exciting to play
new music, isn't it?

521
00:26:54,313 --> 00:26:55,748
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

522
00:26:55,782 --> 00:26:59,118
Great. All right, please,
join the other fellows.

523
00:27:00,519 --> 00:27:03,890
Now, I know you're all
conducting students

524
00:27:03,923 --> 00:27:06,859
of, uh, Mr. Wolfe's,
but how many of you

525
00:27:06,893 --> 00:27:10,029
are also studying composition?

526
00:27:10,062 --> 00:27:11,630
Right, what's your name?

527
00:27:11,664 --> 00:27:13,099
Olive Kerr.

528
00:27:13,132 --> 00:27:15,668
All right, Olive. Uh...

529
00:27:15,702 --> 00:27:18,170
What do you make of what
we've just been listening to?

530
00:27:18,204 --> 00:27:19,972
It's pretty awesome.

531
00:27:20,006 --> 00:27:23,242
I mean, there's incredible
atonal tension.

532
00:27:23,275 --> 00:27:25,544
I agree about the tension part.

533
00:27:25,577 --> 00:27:29,448
Now, you can intellectually
contemplate, or masturbate,

534
00:27:29,481 --> 00:27:33,185
about the felicity
of the so-called "atonal,"

535
00:27:33,219 --> 00:27:39,058
but the important question here
is: What are you conducting?

536
00:27:39,091 --> 00:27:40,326
What is the effect?

537
00:27:40,359 --> 00:27:43,329
What is it actually doing to me?

538
00:27:43,362 --> 00:27:47,199
Good music can be
as ornate as a cathedral

539
00:27:47,233 --> 00:27:49,468
or bare as a potting shed

540
00:27:49,501 --> 00:27:52,972
so long as it allows you to
answer both those questions.

541
00:27:53,005 --> 00:27:55,174
-(claps hands)
-Max.

542
00:27:55,207 --> 00:27:57,543
Come on, what do you think?

543
00:28:00,479 --> 00:28:05,351
When... Anna Thorvaldsdóttir
gave her master class,

544
00:28:05,384 --> 00:28:09,221
she said she was often
influenced by the form

545
00:28:09,255 --> 00:28:14,693
and structure of landscapes
and nature she grew up within.

546
00:28:14,727 --> 00:28:17,296
But I'm not sure
she was interested per se

547
00:28:17,329 --> 00:28:20,432
in, uh, describing
those actual sounds.

548
00:28:20,466 --> 00:28:23,169
Very <i>Punkt Kontra Punkt.</i> 

549
00:28:24,170 --> 00:28:25,805
Yes.

550
00:28:25,838 --> 00:28:30,709
The intent of her composition
is vague, to say the least.

551
00:28:30,743 --> 00:28:35,647
So, if her intent is vague,
how do you, as a conductor,

552
00:28:35,681 --> 00:28:39,185
have a point of view
about anything?

553
00:28:39,218 --> 00:28:40,820
Now, to be fair, I mean,

554
00:28:40,853 --> 00:28:43,155
there are times when you will
simply have no choice.

555
00:28:43,189 --> 00:28:45,858
And you will be made to stand
in front of an orchestra

556
00:28:45,892 --> 00:28:49,128
and pretend that there are
these invisible structures.

557
00:28:49,161 --> 00:28:52,264
But my prayer for you

558
00:28:52,298 --> 00:28:54,433
is that you will be spared
the embarrassment

559
00:28:54,466 --> 00:28:56,735
of standing on the podium
with a 4'33",

560
00:28:56,769 --> 00:28:59,371
trying to sell a car
without an engine.

561
00:28:59,405 --> 00:29:01,507
Because now, my friends,

562
00:29:01,540 --> 00:29:04,777
now is the time to conduct music

563
00:29:04,811 --> 00:29:08,314
that actually requires
something of you.

564
00:29:08,347 --> 00:29:09,949
You know,
music that everybody knows

565
00:29:09,982 --> 00:29:14,620
but will hear differently
when you interpret it for them.

566
00:29:14,653 --> 00:29:18,290
For instance, Max,
why not a Kyrie?

567
00:29:18,324 --> 00:29:23,495
You know, like, uh, something
like Bach's <i>Mass in B minor.</i> 

568
00:29:23,529 --> 00:29:25,197
(chuckles nervously)

569
00:29:25,231 --> 00:29:27,166
I'm not really into Bach.

570
00:29:27,199 --> 00:29:29,969
-You're not into Bach?
-Mm-hmm.

571
00:29:30,002 --> 00:29:31,804
Oh, Max.

572
00:29:32,671 --> 00:29:34,907
Have you read
the Schweitzer book?

573
00:29:34,941 --> 00:29:36,442
No.

574
00:29:36,475 --> 00:29:38,110
Well, you should.

575
00:29:38,144 --> 00:29:40,446
It's an important text.

576
00:29:40,479 --> 00:29:42,882
Now, Antonia Brico thought so.

577
00:29:42,915 --> 00:29:45,784
So much so that she shipped
herself to Equatorial Africa

578
00:29:45,818 --> 00:29:48,654
and canoed up the Congo River
to track Schweitzer down

579
00:29:48,687 --> 00:29:51,790
and ask him to teach her
what he knew about Bach.

580
00:29:51,824 --> 00:29:53,559
I mean, somewhere,
I've got a picture of her

581
00:29:53,592 --> 00:29:56,062
in a, in a pith helmet.

582
00:29:56,095 --> 00:29:57,529
I mean, have you...

583
00:29:57,563 --> 00:30:01,567
have you ever played
or-or conducted Bach?

584
00:30:01,600 --> 00:30:07,239
Honestly, as a BIPOC,
pangender person,

585
00:30:07,273 --> 00:30:08,941
I would say Bach's
misogynistic life

586
00:30:08,975 --> 00:30:12,144
makes it kind of impossible
for me

587
00:30:12,178 --> 00:30:14,580
to take his music seriously.

588
00:30:15,982 --> 00:30:17,749
Come on.

589
00:30:17,783 --> 00:30:20,719
What do... what do...
what do you mean by that?

590
00:30:20,752 --> 00:30:24,656
Well, didn't he sire,
like, 20 kids?

591
00:30:24,690 --> 00:30:26,859
Yes, that's documented.

592
00:30:26,893 --> 00:30:30,629
Along with a considerable
amount of music.

593
00:30:30,662 --> 00:30:32,999
But I'm sorry,
I'm... I'm unclear

594
00:30:33,032 --> 00:30:35,667
as to what his prodigious
skills in the marital bed

595
00:30:35,701 --> 00:30:39,005
have to do with B minor.

596
00:30:39,038 --> 00:30:40,472
Sure.

597
00:30:40,506 --> 00:30:43,142
All right, whatever.
That's-that's your choice.

598
00:30:43,175 --> 00:30:46,045
I mean, after all, "a soul
selects her own society."

599
00:30:46,078 --> 00:30:48,881
But remember, the flip side
of that selection

600
00:30:48,915 --> 00:30:51,850
closes the valves
of one's attention.

601
00:30:51,884 --> 00:30:56,188
Now, of course,
siloing what is acceptable

602
00:30:56,222 --> 00:30:59,591
or not acceptable
is a basic construct of many,

603
00:30:59,625 --> 00:31:01,994
if not most,
symphony orchestras today,

604
00:31:02,028 --> 00:31:04,096
who see it
as their imperial right

605
00:31:04,130 --> 00:31:05,697
to curate for the cretins.

606
00:31:05,731 --> 00:31:07,699
So, slippery as it is,

607
00:31:07,733 --> 00:31:11,337
there is some merit
in examining Max's allergy.

608
00:31:11,370 --> 00:31:14,806
Can classical music
written by a bunch of straight,

609
00:31:14,840 --> 00:31:18,010
Austro-German, churchgoing
white guys exalt us,

610
00:31:18,044 --> 00:31:20,612
individually
as-as well as collectively,

611
00:31:20,646 --> 00:31:24,650
and who, may I ask,
gets to decide that?

612
00:31:25,617 --> 00:31:28,087
(sighs)
You know, what about Beethoven?

613
00:31:28,120 --> 00:31:29,888
You into him?

614
00:31:29,922 --> 00:31:32,758
Because for me,
as a U-Haul lesbian,

615
00:31:32,791 --> 00:31:35,995
I'm... I'm not too sure
about old Ludwig.

616
00:31:37,096 --> 00:31:40,499
But then, I face him.

617
00:31:40,532 --> 00:31:42,734
And I find myself nose-to-nose

618
00:31:42,768 --> 00:31:47,139
with his magnitude
and inevitability.

619
00:31:49,541 --> 00:31:52,544
Come on, Max. Indulge me.

620
00:31:52,578 --> 00:31:56,048
Let's allow Bach a similar gaze.

621
00:31:56,082 --> 00:31:57,316
(inhales deeply)

622
00:31:57,349 --> 00:32:00,719
(playing Bach's Präludium
und Fuge C-Dur. BWV 846)

623
00:32:00,752 --> 00:32:02,054
Sit.

624
00:32:04,890 --> 00:32:07,960
Now, this is all
filigree, right?

625
00:32:07,994 --> 00:32:12,764
I mean, it could be
a first-year piano student.

626
00:32:12,798 --> 00:32:17,436
* Or Schroeder playing
for Lucy. *

627
00:32:19,405 --> 00:32:21,807
Or Glenn Gould, for that matter.

628
00:32:26,412 --> 00:32:28,880
Now, it's not until
it changes...

629
00:32:29,915 --> 00:32:31,483
... when you get inside it,

630
00:32:31,517 --> 00:32:33,085
that you hear what it really is.

631
00:32:33,119 --> 00:32:34,853
It's a question.

632
00:32:37,256 --> 00:32:39,158
And an answer.

633
00:32:40,792 --> 00:32:43,595
Which begs another question.

634
00:32:45,631 --> 00:32:48,000
There's a humility in Bach.

635
00:32:48,034 --> 00:32:51,937
He's not pretending
he's certain about anything.

636
00:32:51,970 --> 00:32:54,906
'Cause he knows
that it's always the question

637
00:32:54,940 --> 00:32:57,943
that involves the listener.

638
00:32:57,976 --> 00:33:01,080
It's never the answer, right?

639
00:33:01,113 --> 00:33:04,783
Now, the big question
for you is:

640
00:33:04,816 --> 00:33:07,119
(growling):
What do you think, Max?

641
00:33:11,157 --> 00:33:13,125
(exhales)

642
00:33:13,159 --> 00:33:15,194
You play really well.

643
00:33:15,227 --> 00:33:21,467
But nowadays, white, male, cis
composers, just not my thing.

644
00:33:21,500 --> 00:33:25,737
Don't be so eager
to be offended.

645
00:33:25,771 --> 00:33:27,906
The narcissism
of small differences

646
00:33:27,939 --> 00:33:30,676
leads to the most boring
conformity.

647
00:33:30,709 --> 00:33:32,744
I guess Edgard Varèse is okay.

648
00:33:32,778 --> 00:33:34,713
I mean, I like "Arcana," anyway.

649
00:33:34,746 --> 00:33:37,749
Oh, well, then you must be
aware that Varèse

650
00:33:37,783 --> 00:33:40,052
once famously stated that jazz

651
00:33:40,086 --> 00:33:44,323
was "a Negro product
exploited by the Jews."

652
00:33:44,356 --> 00:33:47,025
Didn't stop Jerry Goldsmith
from ripping him off

653
00:33:47,059 --> 00:33:49,195
for his
 <i>Planet of the Apes</i> score.

654
00:33:49,228 --> 00:33:51,830
It's kind of a perfect insult,
don't you think?

655
00:33:51,863 --> 00:33:55,601
But you see, the problem
with enrolling yourself

656
00:33:55,634 --> 00:33:58,104
as an ultrasonic epistemic
dissident

657
00:33:58,137 --> 00:34:01,807
is that if Bach's talent
can be reduced to his gender,

658
00:34:01,840 --> 00:34:04,843
birth country, religion,
sexuality, and so on,

659
00:34:04,876 --> 00:34:07,479
then so can yours.

660
00:34:07,513 --> 00:34:11,083
Now, someday, Max,
when you go out into the world

661
00:34:11,117 --> 00:34:14,620
and you guest conduct
for a major or minor orchestra,

662
00:34:14,653 --> 00:34:17,789
you may notice that the players
have more than light bulbs

663
00:34:17,823 --> 00:34:20,292
and music on their stands.

664
00:34:20,326 --> 00:34:23,695
They will also have been
handed rating sheets,

665
00:34:23,729 --> 00:34:26,665
the purpose of which
is to rate you.

666
00:34:26,698 --> 00:34:29,034
Now, what kind of criteria

667
00:34:29,067 --> 00:34:31,570
would you hope that they would
use to do this?

668
00:34:31,603 --> 00:34:35,006
Your score reading and stick
technique, or something else?

669
00:34:37,909 --> 00:34:41,480
All right, everyone,
using Max's criteria,

670
00:34:41,513 --> 00:34:44,082
let's consider Max's thing.

671
00:34:44,116 --> 00:34:46,918
In this case,
Anna Thorvaldsdóttir.

672
00:34:46,952 --> 00:34:50,722
Now, can we agree on two pieces
of observation?

673
00:34:50,756 --> 00:34:53,225
One, that Anna was born
in Iceland.

674
00:34:53,259 --> 00:34:55,561
And two, that she is,
in a, I don't know,

675
00:34:55,594 --> 00:34:58,330
Waldorf teacher kinda way,
a superhot young woman.

676
00:34:58,364 --> 00:35:00,166
Show of hands.

677
00:35:00,199 --> 00:35:02,501
All right,
now let's turn our gaze

678
00:35:02,534 --> 00:35:04,436
back to the piano bench up there

679
00:35:04,470 --> 00:35:07,839
and see if we can square
how any of those things

680
00:35:07,873 --> 00:35:12,178
possibly relate to the person
we see seated before us.

681
00:35:12,211 --> 00:35:14,079
(lid slams shut)

682
00:35:16,848 --> 00:35:18,750
Oh, where are you going?

683
00:35:22,388 --> 00:35:23,789
You're a fucking bitch.

684
00:35:23,822 --> 00:35:25,324
(Tár grunts)

685
00:35:25,357 --> 00:35:27,326
And you are a robot.

686
00:35:27,359 --> 00:35:29,928
I mean, unfortunately,
the architect of your soul

687
00:35:29,961 --> 00:35:32,598
appears to be social media.

688
00:35:32,631 --> 00:35:35,967
You want to dance the mask,
you must service the composer.

689
00:35:36,001 --> 00:35:37,303
You gotta sublimate yourself,

690
00:35:37,336 --> 00:35:40,372
your ego, and, yes,
your identity.

691
00:35:40,406 --> 00:35:42,974
You must, in fact, stand
in front of the public and God

692
00:35:43,008 --> 00:35:45,844
and obliterate yourself.

693
00:35:47,879 --> 00:35:49,615
(sighs):
All right.

694
00:35:49,648 --> 00:35:51,317
ALEC BALDWIN (over computer):
During the lockdown,

695
00:35:51,350 --> 00:35:53,685
you did something
I thought remarkable.

696
00:35:53,719 --> 00:35:55,321
You made music for free.

697
00:35:55,354 --> 00:35:58,023
Anyone at all could stream
Berlin performances

698
00:35:58,056 --> 00:36:00,592
without ever paying a dime.

699
00:36:00,626 --> 00:36:02,528
TÁR:
Well, that-that was a...

700
00:36:02,561 --> 00:36:05,897
it's a democratically made
decision by the players.

701
00:36:05,931 --> 00:36:10,135
And though I-I wish I could
claim the idea was mine,

702
00:36:10,168 --> 00:36:13,705
it really did spring from
the heart of Sharon Goodnow.

703
00:36:13,739 --> 00:36:15,073
BALDWIN:
Sharon is your partner.

704
00:36:15,106 --> 00:36:16,442
You have a child together,

705
00:36:16,475 --> 00:36:19,177
and she's also the
concertmaster for Berlin.

706
00:36:19,211 --> 00:36:21,146
-Does that ever...
-Yes, that's right.

707
00:36:21,179 --> 00:36:22,981
... complicate things for you?

708
00:36:23,014 --> 00:36:24,950
Your work getting into your
home or the other way ar...?

709
00:36:24,983 --> 00:36:27,219
(indistinct chatter)

710
00:36:38,830 --> 00:36:40,198
FRANCESCA:
Jake said he was certain

711
00:36:40,232 --> 00:36:42,000
you'd be happy with the drape
of the seat.

712
00:36:42,033 --> 00:36:43,502
I will be... (sighs)

713
00:36:43,535 --> 00:36:46,037
... if I can keep the fat off
until next month.

714
00:36:46,071 --> 00:36:48,907
(laughs):
You never gain weight.

715
00:36:49,675 --> 00:36:51,443
(laughs softly)

716
00:36:52,244 --> 00:36:54,413
Your... your mother texted me.

717
00:36:54,446 --> 00:36:56,915
She knows you're busy
but is hoping to drop by.

718
00:36:56,948 --> 00:36:58,450
(clears throat nervously)

719
00:36:58,484 --> 00:37:00,085
Next trip.

720
00:37:00,118 --> 00:37:02,454
What are you thinking
for dinner?

721
00:37:02,488 --> 00:37:04,055
Uh, no.

722
00:37:04,089 --> 00:37:06,958
No, I'm-I'm gonna stay in
and put this piano to good use.

723
00:37:06,992 --> 00:37:10,562
I'm suspicious of the E natural
in the cello line.

724
00:37:10,596 --> 00:37:13,832
Doesn't it sound like
warmed-over Charles Ives to you?

725
00:37:13,865 --> 00:37:15,834
Not-not at all.

726
00:37:15,867 --> 00:37:17,836
But don't worry,
I'll call Houston.

727
00:37:17,869 --> 00:37:19,271
They'll be flexible.

728
00:37:19,305 --> 00:37:21,873
(sighs) You must have
some New Haven friends

729
00:37:21,907 --> 00:37:24,042
you want to see tonight?

730
00:37:24,075 --> 00:37:26,378
(chuckles):
No. Not really.

731
00:37:26,412 --> 00:37:28,013
(Tár sighs, sniffs)

732
00:37:28,046 --> 00:37:31,082
Should I stop by later
for notes?

733
00:37:31,116 --> 00:37:33,218
No, that won't be necessary.

734
00:37:33,251 --> 00:37:36,087
-(playing dramatic melody)
-(quietly): Okay.

735
00:37:38,524 --> 00:37:43,995
