Now, that's not true.

993
00:54:43,548 --> 00:54:46,283
I'd never have the position
here were it not for you.

994
00:54:46,317 --> 00:54:48,886
Then you'd be in London,
New York.

995
00:54:48,919 --> 00:54:50,888
They're not Berlin.

996
00:54:51,989 --> 00:54:54,492
Besides, I'm not sure
what Sharon would do,

997
00:54:54,525 --> 00:54:55,726
were we ever to leave.

998
00:54:55,760 --> 00:54:57,562
She's so close with her family.

999
00:54:57,595 --> 00:55:01,131
Ah, yeah, the Goodnow sisters.

1000
00:55:01,165 --> 00:55:03,801
I remember the elder one
being an absolute ball-breaker

1001
00:55:03,834 --> 00:55:06,937
while she still held sway at DG.

1002
00:55:06,971 --> 00:55:10,875
-Heike is a woman
of many opinions. -Oh.

1003
00:55:10,908 --> 00:55:12,142
And that voice.

1004
00:55:12,176 --> 00:55:13,611
I mean, the signal-to-noise
ratio,

1005
00:55:13,644 --> 00:55:15,580
-it's unbearable.
-(chuckles)

1006
00:55:15,613 --> 00:55:17,948
I've had to bolt-hole
at my old place in town

1007
00:55:17,982 --> 00:55:20,451
to get any writing done.

1008
00:55:20,485 --> 00:55:22,052
Schopenhauer measured
a man's intelligence

1009
00:55:22,086 --> 00:55:24,321
against his sensitivity
to noise.

1010
00:55:24,355 --> 00:55:25,723
(chuckles)

1011
00:55:25,756 --> 00:55:28,793
Didn't he once also throw
a woman down a flight of stairs

1012
00:55:28,826 --> 00:55:30,461
who later sued him?

1013
00:55:30,495 --> 00:55:31,662
(chuckles):
Yes.

1014
00:55:31,696 --> 00:55:33,230
Although, it's unclear

1015
00:55:33,263 --> 00:55:34,832
this private
and personal failing

1016
00:55:34,865 --> 00:55:37,635
is at all relevant to his work.

1017
00:55:37,668 --> 00:55:39,904
(both chuckling)

1018
00:55:39,937 --> 00:55:42,172
(tires squeal)

1019
00:55:45,009 --> 00:55:47,077
You're late.

1020
00:55:47,111 --> 00:55:48,646
(driver speaking German)

1021
00:55:48,679 --> 00:55:49,847
Here, give me your stick.

1022
00:55:49,880 --> 00:55:51,616
-Thank you.
-I've got it.

1023
00:55:51,649 --> 00:55:54,885
(distant siren wailing)

1024
00:56:00,691 --> 00:56:02,927
(meditative breaths)

1025
00:56:23,080 --> 00:56:25,315
*

1026
00:56:36,627 --> 00:56:39,063
(exhaling)

1027
00:56:39,096 --> 00:56:41,331
-(inhales deeply)
-*

1028
00:56:47,638 --> 00:56:49,874
(bell chiming in distance)

1029
00:56:56,747 --> 00:56:58,983
(chiming continues)

1030
00:57:02,720 --> 00:57:05,055
(Tár mimicking chiming)

1031
00:57:10,861 --> 00:57:12,830
(plays two notes
matching bell chime)

1032
00:57:12,863 --> 00:57:15,399
(Tár mimics chiming)

1033
00:57:28,613 --> 00:57:30,648
(exhales)

1034
00:57:32,717 --> 00:57:34,318
(exhales)

1035
00:57:36,921 --> 00:57:38,556
(shrill scream in distance)

1036
00:57:39,924 --> 00:57:42,159
(woman continues screaming)

1037
00:57:44,562 --> 00:57:46,597
(siren wailing)

1038
00:57:48,833 --> 00:57:51,068
(screaming continues)

1039
00:58:04,815 --> 00:58:06,784
(screaming continues)

1040
00:58:06,817 --> 00:58:09,053
(Sharon breathing rhythmically)

1041
00:58:19,263 --> 00:58:21,498
(bell chiming in distance)

1042
00:58:26,637 --> 00:58:28,272
(sighs)

1043
00:58:45,455 --> 00:58:46,523
(sighs)

1044
00:58:46,557 --> 00:58:48,993
(plays two notes
matching bell chime)

1045
00:58:55,465 --> 00:58:57,702
(playing gentle melody)

1046
00:59:04,408 --> 00:59:07,645
(orchestra playing Mahler
Symphony No. 5 Trauermarsch)

1047
00:59:21,291 --> 00:59:23,794
(tempo slows)

1048
00:59:38,008 --> 00:59:40,277
Okay. Uh...

1049
00:59:41,779 --> 00:59:43,013
 <i>Gut, gut.</i> 

1050
00:59:43,047 --> 00:59:45,015
(speaking German)

1051
00:59:45,883 --> 00:59:48,318
... Christian...
(continues speaking German)

1052
00:59:52,189 --> 00:59:53,891
Okay?

1053
00:59:53,924 --> 00:59:56,026
Uh, but it's also...

1054
00:59:56,060 --> 00:59:57,227
It's like we're hearing it

1055
00:59:57,261 --> 00:59:59,864
from a very, very great
distance.

1056
00:59:59,897 --> 01:00:05,269
So it's... (vocalizing)

1057
01:00:05,302 --> 01:00:06,503
Ju... Uh...

1058
01:00:06,536 --> 01:00:08,205
Sorry. <i>Ist</i> Harald <i>da?</i> 

1059
01:00:08,238 --> 01:00:09,606
(Harald speaks German)

1060
01:00:09,640 --> 01:00:10,808
(speaks German)

1061
01:00:10,841 --> 01:00:13,110
Harald? I was just wondering
if you might, um,

1062
01:00:13,143 --> 01:00:15,713
uh, quickly rig something up
for us?

1063
01:00:16,513 --> 01:00:18,749
(trumpet solo playing)

1064
01:00:25,089 --> 01:00:27,324
*

1065
01:00:31,696 --> 01:00:33,731
(playing louder)

1066
01:00:40,738 --> 01:00:44,174
(cymbals crash,
orchestra ends with flourish)

1067
01:00:46,677 --> 01:00:48,645
 <i>Gut, gut, gut.</i> (speaks German)

1068
01:00:48,679 --> 01:00:50,915
-Harald?
-(Harald speaks German)

1069
01:00:50,948 --> 01:00:52,850
Uh, we'll want the same
backstage setup

1070
01:00:52,883 --> 01:00:54,051
for the live recording.

1071
01:00:54,084 --> 01:00:55,953
(quietly):
One, two, one.

1072
01:00:55,986 --> 01:00:58,789
(orchestra playing
jaunty classical music)

1073
01:01:15,405 --> 01:01:17,041
-(speaks indistinctly)
-(playing stops)

1074
01:01:17,074 --> 01:01:20,277
(speaking German)

1075
01:01:23,647 --> 01:01:26,483
Okay? Looks great, but...
(clears throat)

1076
01:01:26,516 --> 01:01:27,985
... we need to hear it.

1077
01:01:28,018 --> 01:01:30,755
Okay? It's not...
(vocalizing)

1078
01:01:30,788 --> 01:01:32,089
(vocalizing intensifies)

1079
01:01:32,122 --> 01:01:33,323
Hey.

1080
01:01:33,357 --> 01:01:34,725
-(speaking low)
-(snaps fingers)

1081
01:01:34,759 --> 01:01:36,626
(speaking German)

1082
01:01:40,464 --> 01:01:42,032
 <i>Ja?</i> (whooshes)

1083
01:01:42,066 --> 01:01:44,401
Okay? (puffing)

1084
01:01:45,836 --> 01:01:47,805
(speaks German)

1085
01:01:50,674 --> 01:01:52,709
*

1086
01:01:57,581 --> 01:01:59,750
No. (speaks German)

1087
01:01:59,784 --> 01:02:01,218
Bah! (exhales)

1088
01:02:02,019 --> 01:02:03,587
It's-it's much too slow.

1089
01:02:04,388 --> 01:02:06,490
(speaking German)

1090
01:02:10,460 --> 01:02:12,129
(plays sharp chords)

1091
01:02:12,162 --> 01:02:13,798
Mm-hmm.

1092
01:02:13,831 --> 01:02:16,000
Okay.

1093
01:02:16,033 --> 01:02:17,701
Okay, tutti.

1094
01:02:17,734 --> 01:02:19,203
Uh...

1095
01:02:19,236 --> 01:02:21,205
(speaking German)

1096
01:02:21,238 --> 01:02:23,407
How are things feeling up here?

1097
01:02:23,440 --> 01:02:24,641
Fine, yeah.

1098
01:02:24,674 --> 01:02:26,443
Yeah, actually great, but, uh,

1099
01:02:26,476 --> 01:02:28,745
it's a shame we don't record
this one direct-to-disk.

1100
01:02:28,779 --> 01:02:31,681
(groans): Oh. It's criminal,
is more like it.

1101
01:02:32,716 --> 01:02:34,451
Will you shoot me the MP3s?

1102
01:02:34,484 --> 01:02:36,286
Yeah, sure,
but don't you want WAV files?

1103
01:02:36,320 --> 01:02:39,924
No, just think what people
will actually be streaming.

1104
01:02:39,957 --> 01:02:41,225
Uh, what about video?

1105
01:02:41,258 --> 01:02:43,193
Yes, yes.
Uh, stage left A camera.

1106
01:02:43,227 --> 01:02:44,661
-Okay.
-All right. Thanks, guys.

1107
01:02:44,694 --> 01:02:46,330
Okay. Uh, bye.
You're quite welcome.

1108
01:02:46,363 --> 01:02:48,632
(speaking German)

1109
01:02:48,665 --> 01:02:50,100
-SHARON: There?
-TÁR: Yeah.

1110
01:02:50,134 --> 01:02:51,936
You want us to come,
to come in stronger there?

1111
01:02:51,969 --> 01:02:53,437
-FRANCESCA: Okay, then yeah.
-TÁR: Yeah.

1112
01:02:53,470 --> 01:02:54,939
Here, 'cause the reigning
dynamic is forte,

1113
01:02:54,972 --> 01:02:56,540
-which is not good.
-(Sebastian clears throat)

1114
01:02:56,573 --> 01:02:58,075
-FRANCESCA: Hmm.
-TÁR: Yeah?

1115
01:02:58,108 --> 01:03:01,378
(whispering): Yeah. Um, just
one small thing, Maestro.

1116
01:03:01,411 --> 01:03:04,048
During the scherzo, um,

1117
01:03:04,081 --> 01:03:07,417
th-th-the clarinet solo's
still a bit too loud.

1118
01:03:07,451 --> 01:03:09,453
It should really be
an accompanying figure

1119
01:03:09,486 --> 01:03:12,522
-to the first violins.
-TÁR: Hmm.

1120
01:03:12,556 --> 01:03:16,026
But apart from that, I'd say
we're in very good shape.

1121
01:03:16,060 --> 01:03:17,694
Thank you, Sebastian.

1122
01:03:17,727 --> 01:03:19,930
Thank you. (clears throat)

1123
01:03:25,235 --> 01:03:26,904
Accurate assessment?

1124
01:03:26,937 --> 01:03:28,705
I don't think so.

1125
01:03:28,738 --> 01:03:31,976
The clarinet is marked piano,
and we are marked pianissimo.

1126
01:03:32,009 --> 01:03:34,078
Sebastian likes to sit
in the stalls,

1127
01:03:34,111 --> 01:03:37,581
but there's no problem
with the balance in the circle.

1128
01:03:37,614 --> 01:03:39,583
TÁR:
Mm-hmm.

1129
01:03:40,784 --> 01:03:42,252
Mm-hmm.

1130
01:03:42,286 --> 01:03:44,321
Something a bit more playful.

1131
01:03:44,354 --> 01:03:45,856
Mm-hmm.

1132
01:03:49,793 --> 01:03:52,129
Oh, and here's something
Tanya and I did with Gustavo.

1133
01:03:52,162 --> 01:03:53,730
I think it's very powerful.

1134
01:03:53,763 --> 01:03:55,933
Yes, it's-it's really wonderful
work, uh, Karl.

1135
01:03:55,966 --> 01:03:57,767
I'm just wondering
if we might try something

1136
01:03:57,801 --> 01:04:00,905
a little less, uh, considered.

1137
01:04:03,540 --> 01:04:06,010
Something simple like this?

1138
01:04:06,043 --> 01:04:07,377
Hmm?

1139
01:04:07,411 --> 01:04:09,813
I'm not sure how you would
want to light it.

1140
01:04:09,846 --> 01:04:12,716
Have Harald dim
the houselights to half.

1141
01:04:13,583 --> 01:04:16,320
Houselights down half, please.

1142
01:04:19,957 --> 01:04:21,791
KARL:
I mean, we could make it work,

1143
01:04:21,825 --> 01:04:23,493
but we'd have to bring in
some lights.

1144
01:04:23,527 --> 01:04:25,562
TANYA:
Mm-hmm.

1145
01:04:28,532 --> 01:04:30,134
KARL: If we want to do
something like this,

1146
01:04:30,167 --> 01:04:32,469
uh, we'll have to bring
the hot lights

1147
01:04:32,502 --> 01:04:34,538
next week, Tanya--
forget about the strobes.

1148
01:04:34,571 --> 01:04:36,840
-TANYA: Hmm.
-(departing footsteps)

1149
01:04:37,641 --> 01:04:39,109
TÁR:
Thank you for waiting.

1150
01:04:39,143 --> 01:04:40,710
Of course, Maestro.

1151
01:04:40,744 --> 01:04:43,813
How are we feeling
about today's rehearsal?

1152
01:04:43,847 --> 01:04:47,517
Well, Sebastian thinks
your solo in the scherzo

1153
01:04:47,551 --> 01:04:49,853
is, uh, a bit loud.

1154
01:04:49,886 --> 01:04:51,055
It's possible.

1155
01:04:51,088 --> 01:04:52,923
Hmm. I don't agree.

1156
01:04:52,957 --> 01:04:56,193
Your dynamic marking is higher
than that of the first violin.

1157
01:04:56,226 --> 01:04:57,627
Yes, that's true.

1158
01:04:57,661 --> 01:04:59,429
(sighs heavily) Look.

1159
01:04:59,463 --> 01:05:03,200
Sebastian's getting old, Knut.

1160
01:05:03,233 --> 01:05:04,834
I'm rotating him out.

1161
01:05:05,635 --> 01:05:07,871
You're the first to know.

1162
01:05:10,941 --> 01:05:13,110
Well...

1163
01:05:14,979 --> 01:05:18,315
Then I will organize a caucus,
and we'll take a vote.

1164
01:05:18,348 --> 01:05:21,285
No. No, you won't.

1165
01:05:21,318 --> 01:05:23,753
A vote must be taken.

1166
01:05:23,787 --> 01:05:25,922
I am familiar with
the electoral conclave.

1167
01:05:25,956 --> 01:05:28,192
But the appointment
of the assistant conductor

1168
01:05:28,225 --> 01:05:30,694
is entirely my decision.

1169
01:05:30,727 --> 01:05:32,296
(Knut inhales deeply)

1170
01:05:32,329 --> 01:05:33,730
Yes.

1171
01:05:33,763 --> 01:05:37,001
So, I can count on your
support with the others?

1172
01:05:37,034 --> 01:05:38,935
(chuckles softly)

1173
01:05:38,969 --> 01:05:40,204
Yes.

1174
01:05:40,237 --> 01:05:41,571
Good.

1175
01:05:41,605 --> 01:05:42,806
Who will you replace him with?

1176
01:05:42,839 --> 01:05:44,841
Oh. I'm considering a few names,

1177
01:05:44,874 --> 01:05:47,911
but the main thing is we
proceed with this immediately.

1178
01:05:47,944 --> 01:05:50,247
KNUT:
I understand.

1179
01:05:50,280 --> 01:05:52,682
Maestro, uh, the other players
would like to know

1180
01:05:52,716 --> 01:05:54,318
if you have chosen
the companion piece.

1181
01:05:54,351 --> 01:05:56,120
 <i>Ach!</i> 

1182
01:05:58,255 --> 01:05:59,956
KNUT:
Okay. <i>Danke.</i> 

1183
01:06:12,469 --> 01:06:14,771
(panting)

1184
01:06:24,248 --> 01:06:25,949
(short whistle)

1185
01:06:26,916 --> 01:06:27,751
Oh.

1186
01:06:27,784 --> 01:06:30,220
-I...
-It's okay.

1187
01:06:30,254 --> 01:06:31,888
 <i>Danke.</i> 

1188
01:06:47,337 --> 01:06:49,573
(playing simple melody)

1189
01:06:54,744 --> 01:06:56,613
(light knocking)

1190
01:06:57,547 --> 01:07:03,220
* Changing major to minor.

1191
01:07:04,488 --> 01:07:06,490
(Francesca clears her throat)

1192
01:07:06,523 --> 01:07:08,792
Uh, I'm sorry, I knocked.

1193
01:07:10,094 --> 01:07:13,130
I knew you wanted your keys
back as quickly as possible.

1194
01:07:13,163 --> 01:07:14,464
Yes, thanks.

1195
01:07:14,498 --> 01:07:16,200
Did you use the company card?

1196
01:07:16,233 --> 01:07:17,367
Yeah.

1197
01:07:17,401 --> 01:07:18,868
We can use it for your, um...

1198
01:07:18,902 --> 01:07:20,937
(clears throat)
... your taxi home.

1199
01:07:25,242 --> 01:07:27,077
Yeah. It's all right.

1200
01:07:27,111 --> 01:07:28,978
You can go.

1201
01:07:30,013 --> 01:07:33,650
Uh, it wasn't just the keys.

1202
01:07:36,386 --> 01:07:39,256
I-I need someone to hold me.

1203
01:07:41,358 --> 01:07:43,927
This isn't the place, Francesca.

1204
01:07:45,229 --> 01:07:47,597
You're... (stammers)
That's not about...

1205
01:07:47,631 --> 01:07:49,032
(sniffles)

1206
01:07:49,065 --> 01:07:50,967
I just...

1207
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:54,238
I just got this from someone
over at Accordion.

1208
01:07:56,373 --> 01:07:58,608
(breath trembling)

1209
01:08:06,316 --> 01:08:07,784
Oh, no.

1210
01:08:07,817 --> 01:08:10,086
(Francesca's breath trembles)

1211
01:08:10,120 --> 01:08:11,955
(sighs):
When did this happen?

1212
01:08:11,988 --> 01:08:14,090
Day before yesterday.

1213
01:08:15,859 --> 01:08:19,263
That email she sent you,
it felt like she was already...

1214
01:08:19,296 --> 01:08:22,266
Delete it. And the rest.

1215
01:08:22,299 --> 01:08:25,569
There's no reason to get
caught up in any intrigue.

1216
01:08:26,603 --> 01:08:29,206
(sniffles)

1217
01:08:29,239 --> 01:08:30,574
(crying)

1218
01:08:30,607 --> 01:08:32,342
Now, now.

1219
01:08:33,943 --> 01:08:38,782
Come on. There's nothing
we could have done to stop her.

1220
01:08:38,815 --> 01:08:41,485
She wasn't one of us.

1221
01:08:41,518 --> 01:08:43,753
(crying continues)

1222
01:08:52,729 --> 01:08:54,864
(sniffles)

1223
01:08:56,833 --> 01:09:00,504
I can't stop thinking about
our trip up the Ucayali.

1224
01:09:00,537 --> 01:09:01,938
TÁR:
Hmm.

1225
01:09:01,971 --> 01:09:03,973
-The three of us were so close.
-Yes.

1226
01:09:04,007 --> 01:09:07,311
But that was before
she started making demands.

1227
01:09:09,179 --> 01:09:14,218
There was just something
not quite right about her.

1228
01:09:14,251 --> 01:09:16,720
She had so much promise.

1229
01:09:16,753 --> 01:09:18,522
She did.

1230
01:09:18,555 --> 01:09:20,524
Yes.

1231
01:09:20,557 --> 01:09:22,892
Almost as much as you.

1232
01:09:26,896 --> 01:09:30,133
Now, we have to forget
about her.

1233
01:09:33,670 --> 01:09:35,705
You understand?

1234
01:09:40,577 --> 01:09:42,679
-Right?
-(sniffles)

1235
01:09:45,014 --> 01:09:46,583
-I'm sorry.
-No.

1236
01:09:46,616 --> 01:09:47,984
I know you're working.

1237
01:09:48,017 --> 01:09:49,619
-Oh.
-(sniffles)

1238
01:09:49,653 --> 01:09:50,987
Your... (sniffles)

1239
01:09:51,020 --> 01:09:53,990
Your keys are on
the kitchen table.

1240
01:10:35,365 --> 01:10:37,166
(inhales sharply)

1241
01:10:55,385 --> 01:10:57,421
(gentle melody plays)

1242
01:10:58,221 --> 01:11:00,256
SHARON:
She went straight to sleep.

1243
01:11:00,290 --> 01:11:02,826
(liquid pouring)

1244
01:11:02,859 --> 01:11:05,228
Didn't even have
to hold her foot.

1245
01:11:09,899 --> 01:11:13,269
And she came home
in a much better mood.

1246
01:11:13,303 --> 01:11:15,171
Oh, attagirl.

1247
01:11:15,204 --> 01:11:17,240
*

1248
01:11:19,843 --> 01:11:22,145
(Sharon sighs)

1249
01:11:24,681 --> 01:11:26,683
Met the new cellist today.

1250
01:11:26,716 --> 01:11:29,353
Oh, what was that like?

1251
01:11:29,386 --> 01:11:31,655
Olga Metkina.

1252
01:11:31,688 --> 01:11:33,423
Russian.

1253
01:11:33,457 --> 01:11:35,525
Strong player.

1254
01:11:35,559 --> 01:11:37,794
Good.

1255
01:11:37,827 --> 01:11:40,997
Her facial posture
is a bit much.

1256
01:11:41,030 --> 01:11:42,466
(chuckles):
How so?

1257
01:11:42,499 --> 01:11:44,067
Her legato.

1258
01:11:44,100 --> 01:11:46,536
Looks like she's on
the verge of climaxing.

1259
01:11:46,570 --> 01:11:48,104
(both laughing)

1260
01:11:50,807 --> 01:11:53,042
She is young.

1261
01:11:53,076 --> 01:11:54,978
Ah, so you've met her.

1262
01:11:56,813 --> 01:11:58,448
No, no.

1263
01:11:58,482 --> 01:12:01,050
Uh, Francesca
mentioned something.

1264
01:12:01,084 --> 01:12:03,887
I think she's arranging
a welcome lunch.

1265
01:12:06,089 --> 01:12:08,925
You may want to hold off
on that.

1266
01:12:08,958 --> 01:12:11,828
Her invitation is conditional.

1267
01:12:14,798 --> 01:12:17,467
You have reservations?

1268
01:12:17,501 --> 01:12:19,403
No.

1269
01:12:19,436 --> 01:12:21,871
Not really.

1270
01:12:21,905 --> 01:12:24,474
We need to see if she fits in.

1271
01:12:28,244 --> 01:12:30,514
Did you take your pill?

1272
01:12:31,548 --> 01:12:34,050
No.

1273
01:12:34,083 --> 01:12:37,020
Thank you for reminding me.

1274
01:12:43,660 --> 01:12:45,895
(distant, rhythmic ticking)

1275
01:13:07,784 --> 01:13:10,019
(ticking grows louder)

1276
01:13:20,630 --> 01:13:23,066
(ticking continues
to grow louder)

1277
01:13:40,550 --> 01:13:42,919
(ticking loudly)

1278
01:14:04,207 --> 01:14:06,710
How was Johanna yesterday?

1279
01:14:06,743 --> 01:14:09,212
She stays away now.

1280
01:14:09,245 --> 01:14:11,548
You let me know if that changes.

1281
01:14:14,784 --> 01:14:18,522
Petra, last night, you weren't,
by any chance, in my study?

1282
01:14:19,489 --> 01:14:21,324
-No, Lydia.
-Because you do know

1283
01:14:21,357 --> 01:14:23,660
you're not supposed to be
in there without me.

1284
01:14:23,693 --> 01:14:25,194
I know.

1285
01:14:27,063 --> 01:14:28,998
TÁR:
That's right.

1286
01:14:29,933 --> 01:14:32,268
(quiet rattling)

1287
01:14:32,301 --> 01:14:34,538
(rattling continues)

1288
01:14:38,708 --> 01:14:40,610
(sighs)

1289
01:14:40,644 --> 01:14:43,079
 <i>(orchestra playing</i>
 <i>classical music)</i> 

1290
01:15:02,331 --> 01:15:03,867
S...

1291
01:15:04,634 --> 01:15:06,102
-It's not so simple.
-(music stops)

1292
01:15:06,135 --> 01:15:07,771
It's got...
it's got to be messier.

1293
01:15:07,804 --> 01:15:10,039
(speaking German)

1294
01:15:12,075 --> 01:15:13,409
Okay?

1295
01:15:13,442 --> 01:15:15,679
(continues speaking German)

1296
01:15:22,118 --> 01:15:24,654
A lot of pressure. Okay?

1297
01:15:24,688 --> 01:15:27,423
(speaking German)

1298
01:15:27,456 --> 01:15:28,992
-Okay?
-(musicians chuckling)

1299
01:15:29,025 --> 01:15:30,694
S-So familiar to everyone here.

1300
01:15:30,727 --> 01:15:33,663
It really doesn't help you to
know this piece so well. Okay.

1301
01:15:34,998 --> 01:15:36,733
Same place.

1302
01:15:38,234 --> 01:15:40,469
(classical music resumes)

1303
01:15:49,946 --> 01:15:52,181
(speaking German)

1304
01:16:05,862 --> 01:16:07,363
Please.

1305
01:16:07,396 --> 01:16:09,699
-Please, please, please.
-(music stops)

1306
01:16:09,733 --> 01:16:11,768
You must watch.

1307
01:16:13,002 --> 01:16:15,238
(speaking German)

1308
01:16:16,039 --> 01:16:17,841
Okay?

1309
01:16:17,874 --> 01:16:19,208
It's got to be like, uh,

1310
01:16:19,242 --> 01:16:22,646
just one person
singing their heart out.

1311
01:16:24,914 --> 01:16:27,150
And...

1312
01:16:27,183 --> 01:16:29,418
(speaking German)

1313
01:16:32,956 --> 01:16:34,357
Okay.

1314
01:16:34,390 --> 01:16:36,626
(continues speaking German)

1315
01:16:42,999 --> 01:16:44,500
(sighs):
Okay.

1316
01:16:47,170 --> 01:16:49,272
SEBASTIAN:
(grunts) Maestro.

1317
01:16:49,305 --> 01:16:50,640
What a surprise.

1318
01:16:50,674 --> 01:16:52,408
-I was just having
a spot of lunch. -Hmm.

1319
01:16:52,441 --> 01:16:53,777
C-Can I offer you anything?

1320
01:16:53,810 --> 01:16:55,611
-Uh, no, thank you.
-(pen clicking)

1321
01:16:55,645 --> 01:16:58,247
-Mm, well, some tea, perhaps?
-No, thank you, Sebastian.

1322
01:16:59,048 --> 01:17:02,185
You know, I forget sometimes
just how impressive

1323
01:17:02,218 --> 01:17:04,020
your collection is here.

1324
01:17:04,053 --> 01:17:06,122
Is that Kalinnikov?

1325
01:17:06,155 --> 01:17:07,824
-Yes. (chuckles)
-Ah.

1326
01:17:07,857 --> 01:17:09,693
Isn't he marvelous?

1327
01:17:09,726 --> 01:17:13,096
(laughs)
He belongs in a museum.

1328
01:17:13,129 --> 01:17:15,564
I rescued him
for a hundred rubles

1329
01:17:15,598 --> 01:17:18,101
-from a Kyiv street fair
back in '90. -Huh.

1330
01:17:18,134 --> 01:17:19,903
Right after the Wall came down.

1331
01:17:19,936 --> 01:17:22,371
(sighs) That must really
have been something.

1332
01:17:22,405 --> 01:17:25,541
-Oh, incredible to have
lived through it. -Hmm.

1333
01:17:25,574 --> 01:17:27,911
I'd only just arrived here
with Andris,

1334
01:17:27,944 --> 01:17:31,514
and suddenly the impossible
was possible.

1335
01:17:31,547 --> 01:17:33,116
Yeah.

1336
01:17:34,383 --> 01:17:36,753
I'd like to talk about that.

1337
01:17:36,786 --> 01:17:38,855
-The reunification?
-Uh, no, no.

1338
01:17:38,888 --> 01:17:40,890
But please, sit down.

1339
01:17:40,924 --> 01:17:44,160
No, uh, about the possibility

1340
01:17:44,193 --> 01:17:47,663
of you fronting
a subscription orchestra.

1341
01:17:47,697 --> 01:17:49,132
(chuckles):
But I already do.

1342
01:17:49,165 --> 01:17:51,768
Yes, but not as Kapellmeister.

1343
01:17:53,136 --> 01:17:56,439
If not now,
then when, Sebastian?

1344
01:17:57,807 --> 01:17:59,408
You mean leave Berlin?

1345
01:17:59,442 --> 01:18:02,511
Well, rotate somewhere, yes.

1346
01:18:02,545 --> 01:18:04,948
But this is my home.

1347
01:18:04,981 --> 01:18:08,151
Our only home is the podium.

1348
01:18:08,184 --> 01:18:10,453
We all live out of a suitcase.

1349
01:18:10,486 --> 01:18:12,722
You know that as well as anyone.

1350
01:18:18,928 --> 01:18:21,530
Just think about it.

1351
01:18:21,564 --> 01:18:23,967
Take your time. Mm?

1352
01:18:24,000 --> 01:18:27,236
It's not something
we need to decide now.

1353
01:18:29,973 --> 01:18:31,540
It's the girl, isn't it?

1354
01:18:31,574 --> 01:18:33,276
I'm sorry, what girl?

1355
01:18:33,309 --> 01:18:35,812
Y-You're not asking.

1356
01:18:35,845 --> 01:18:37,646
You're telling.

1357
01:18:37,680 --> 01:18:42,085
I knew as soon as she showed up
that my days here were numbered.

1358
01:18:42,118 --> 01:18:44,954
Andris told me not to worry,
but... (scoffs)

1359
01:18:44,988 --> 01:18:46,622
... I knew.

1360
01:18:46,655 --> 01:18:50,226
I'm sure I don't know
what you're talking about.

1361
01:18:50,259 --> 01:18:51,627
Oh, please.

1362
01:18:51,660 --> 01:18:53,629
Just because
nobody dares breathe it.

1363
01:18:53,662 --> 01:18:55,965
We know the things you do.

1364
01:18:55,999 --> 01:18:58,968
The little favors you grant.

1365
01:18:59,002 --> 01:19:00,403
I'm...

1366
01:19:00,436 --> 01:19:03,606
I really don't know
what to say, Sebastian.

1367
01:19:03,639 --> 01:19:05,875
I mean, you of all people

1368
01:19:05,909 --> 01:19:08,344
have the temerity
to question my integrity?

1369
01:19:08,377 --> 01:19:09,712
No, no.
I-I'm-I'm sorry, Maestro.

1370
01:19:09,745 --> 01:19:11,614
I don't, I don't know
what I'm saying.

1371
01:19:11,647 --> 01:19:14,117
No, no, no, it's clear you know
exactly what you're saying.

1372
01:19:14,150 --> 01:19:16,419
I mean, if that's how
you really feel about me,

1373
01:19:16,452 --> 01:19:18,287
then wouldn't you say
that staying is

1374
01:19:18,321 --> 01:19:19,622
entirely out of the question?

1375
01:19:19,655 --> 01:19:21,724
No, no, please, Maestro.
Please forgive me.

1376
01:19:21,757 --> 01:19:23,059
(sighs) For what?

1377
01:19:23,092 --> 01:19:26,662
Your obsequiousness,
your hypocrisy, your misogamy?

1378
01:19:26,695 --> 01:19:29,665
-I'm not a misogynist!
-Misogamy.

1379
01:19:29,698 --> 01:19:32,301
It's a hatred of marriage.

1380
01:19:33,769 --> 01:19:36,906
Andris is still
very much married.

1381
01:19:37,907 --> 01:19:42,778
And you occupy an apartment
on the same floor, don't you?

1382
01:19:42,812 --> 01:19:46,215
I just don't like
what he's implying.

1383
01:19:47,016 --> 01:19:50,253
It could lead to more than
Chinese whispers.

1384
01:19:50,286 --> 01:19:52,088
I know.

1385
01:19:52,121 --> 01:19:53,589
We barely survived <i>Der Spiegel</i> 

1386
01:19:53,622 --> 01:19:55,859
when you and I
came out together.

1387
01:19:57,260 --> 01:20:01,831
But with Francesca, no one
could point their finger.

1388
01:20:01,865 --> 01:20:04,333
It's not like you two are
in a relationship.

1389
01:20:04,367 --> 01:20:05,701
Yeah, that's true.

1390
01:20:05,734 --> 01:20:08,037
I just...
Turns my stomach to think

1391
01:20:08,071 --> 01:20:10,874
the old robot will be right
about something.

1392
01:20:12,541 --> 01:20:16,545
He's probably already run
to Andris. (scoffs)

1393
01:20:16,579 --> 01:20:20,116
Well, is there someone
other than Francesca

1394
01:20:20,149 --> 01:20:22,385
you feel is more qualified?

1395
01:20:24,988 --> 01:20:27,690
There are others
equal to the task.

1396
01:20:30,226 --> 01:20:32,328
Hmm?

1397
01:20:32,361 --> 01:20:34,630
Maybe wait to decide.

1398
01:20:43,706 --> 01:20:45,408
Where are we at with DG?

1399
01:20:45,441 --> 01:20:49,112
-Uh, I spoke to an assistant
in Boyd Muir's office... -Hmm.

1400
01:20:49,145 --> 01:20:51,915
... who said they weren't sure
why they decided

1401
01:20:51,948 --> 01:20:55,718
on a digital-only set,
what the criteria were.

1402
01:20:55,751 --> 01:20:57,586
-(sighs)
-But I do know they just did

1403
01:20:57,620 --> 01:20:59,255
a full-vinyl pressing
for Long Yu.

1404
01:20:59,288 --> 01:21:01,057
Of course they did.

1405
01:21:01,090 --> 01:21:03,292
The Chinese market's incredible.

1406
01:21:03,326 --> 01:21:05,294
All right. Gloves off.

1407
01:21:05,328 --> 01:21:06,662
I'm going straight to Lucian.

1408
01:21:06,695 --> 01:21:08,031
Maybe he needs to be reminded of

1409
01:21:08,064 --> 01:21:09,999
his Annenberg
Inclusion Initiative.

1410
01:21:10,033 --> 01:21:11,567
(chuckles)

1411
01:21:11,600 --> 01:21:13,002
You've got
his contact details, right?

1412
01:21:13,036 --> 01:21:16,405
Mm-hmm.
I'll send it to you right now.

1413
01:21:17,506 --> 01:21:21,610
(groans)
My machine's misbehaving again.

1414
01:21:21,644 --> 01:21:23,579
I've already spoken to I.T.

1415
01:21:23,612 --> 01:21:25,848
Just here-- let me borrow yours.

1416
01:21:32,956 --> 01:21:34,790
Thank you.

1417
01:21:37,726 --> 01:21:39,662
Where's the matcha?

1418
01:21:47,103 --> 01:21:48,938
(door closes)

1419
01:21:59,182 --> 01:22:01,417
(Tár exhales softly)

1420
01:22:13,496 --> 01:22:15,731
(grunting)

1421
01:22:24,040 --> 01:22:26,175
Ah, I wasn't sure
where you were.

1422
01:22:26,209 --> 01:22:27,977
Was working out a kink.

1423
01:22:28,011 --> 01:22:30,413
The-the matcha's cold.
I-I'll get another.

1424
01:22:30,446 --> 01:22:31,647
It's all right.
I don't need it.

1425
01:22:31,680 --> 01:22:33,916
Let's just keep working.

1426
01:22:35,351 --> 01:22:37,420
(Tár clears throat)

1427
01:22:41,290 --> 01:22:43,292
Francesca, you did as I asked

1428
01:22:43,326 --> 01:22:47,163
and deleted any and all
correspondence with Krista,

1429
01:22:47,196 --> 01:22:48,797
correct?

1430
01:22:50,433 --> 01:22:53,536
Um, I'm not sure.

1431
01:22:54,537 --> 01:22:56,205
Uh, I'm-I'm... I'm not sure.

1432
01:22:56,239 --> 01:22:58,541
I-I'll double-check.

1433
01:23:05,581 --> 01:23:08,551
You know,
Sebastian's leaving us,

1434
01:23:08,584 --> 01:23:10,119
and I wondered if you might, uh,

1435
01:23:10,153 --> 01:23:14,123
compile a list
of suitable replacements.

1436
01:23:18,961 --> 01:23:22,131
Uh, of course, feel free
to add your own name.

1437
01:23:25,234 --> 01:23:27,770
-Thank you.
-(cell phone vibrates)

1438
01:23:29,072 --> 01:23:33,008
Oh, your-your lunch
with the new cellist.

1439
01:23:33,042 --> 01:23:34,110
Oh.

1440
01:23:34,143 --> 01:23:35,544
Meant to have you
reschedule that

1441
01:23:35,578 --> 01:23:37,380
'til after the orchestra votes.

1442
01:23:37,413 --> 01:23:39,482
I'll text her now.

1443
01:23:41,250 --> 01:23:43,286
No, wait. (scoffs)

1444
01:23:43,319 --> 01:23:46,322
Might as well
see what she's made of.

1445
01:23:46,355 --> 01:23:48,057
(Tár sniffles)

1446
01:23:50,259 --> 01:23:52,495
(dishes clinking quietly)

1447
01:23:54,597 --> 01:23:56,832
This food. (chuckles)

1448
01:23:58,267 --> 01:24:02,405
The cucumber salad's,
uh, very good.

1449
01:24:02,438 --> 01:24:04,607
It's kind of the only
real option in this place

1450
01:24:04,640 --> 01:24:06,242
if you're vegetarian.

1451
01:24:06,275 --> 01:24:08,077
Uh, do you eat fish?

1452
01:24:08,111 --> 01:24:09,878
Not really.

1453
01:24:12,581 --> 01:24:15,818
You know, we can go
somewhere else.

1454
01:24:15,851 --> 01:24:17,553
L-Like the Store Kitchen.

1455
01:24:17,586 --> 01:24:20,989
I mean, it's... uh, it's kind
of a silly tradition really

1456
01:24:21,023 --> 01:24:23,126
that new members
are brought here

1457
01:24:23,159 --> 01:24:26,262
to sup with the ghosts
of the past.

1458
01:24:26,295 --> 01:24:29,298
I mean, at some point,
everyone from... from Napoleon

1459
01:24:29,332 --> 01:24:33,302
to Beethoven tucked in for
a meal at one of these tables.

1460
01:24:33,336 --> 01:24:35,671
Yes, and Clara Zetkin.

1461
01:24:35,704 --> 01:24:37,173
I wonder which one.

1462
01:24:37,206 --> 01:24:40,209
Who's that?
It's a, uh, musician?

1463
01:24:40,243 --> 01:24:42,010
No. She helped found

1464
01:24:42,044 --> 01:24:45,013
Social Democratic
women's movement in Germany

1465
01:24:45,047 --> 01:24:48,451
and KPD until
Hitler came to power

1466
01:24:48,484 --> 01:24:51,287
and she was exiled
to Soviet Union.

1467
01:24:51,320 --> 01:24:52,621
Clara Zetkin?

1468
01:24:52,655 --> 01:24:54,056
Yes.

1469
01:24:54,089 --> 01:24:56,592
Every March 8th, we place
flowers at her plaque

1470
01:24:56,625 --> 01:24:59,228
in Kremlin Wall Necropolis.

1471
01:24:59,262 --> 01:25:00,729
Her birthday?

1472
01:25:00,763 --> 01:25:02,865
No, International Women's Day.

1473
01:25:02,898 --> 01:25:04,933
(Olga chuckles)

1474
01:25:06,202 --> 01:25:08,871
-Are you ready, Maestro?
-(pen clicks)

1475
01:25:08,904 --> 01:25:13,209
-Yes, uh... -Yes,
first shashlik, then veal.

1476
01:25:14,042 --> 01:25:16,645
-For you?
-Cucumber salad.

1477
01:25:16,679 --> 01:25:18,046
-Thank you.
-Good choice.

1478
01:25:21,317 --> 01:25:23,386
Some more bread?

1479
01:25:23,419 --> 01:25:25,188
Hmm.

1480
01:25:30,259 --> 01:25:32,127
It's good.
Would you like a bite?

1481
01:25:32,161 --> 01:25:33,829
Oh, no.

1482
01:25:33,862 --> 01:25:35,798
No. Thank you.

1483
01:25:36,832 --> 01:25:38,601
Have you lived in Berlin long?

1484
01:25:38,634 --> 01:25:40,569
No, not at all.

1485
01:25:40,603 --> 01:25:42,104
I have friends in Wicker I visit

1486
01:25:42,137 --> 01:25:44,707
-until I know decision
of orchestra. -Hmm.

1487
01:25:45,574 --> 01:25:47,510
Simonov will hold your place?

1488
01:25:47,543 --> 01:25:50,313
Yes, I think so.
He is my uncle.

1489
01:25:51,647 --> 01:25:53,182
Oh.

1490
01:25:53,216 --> 01:25:55,818
But my dream has always been
to play with Berlin.

1491
01:25:55,851 --> 01:25:57,853
Oh, me, too.

1492
01:25:57,886 --> 01:26:00,122
There's nowhere like it.

1493
01:26:03,626 --> 01:26:07,296
I imagine, uh, Rostropovich
is a hero of yours.

1494
01:26:08,531 --> 01:26:10,766
Well, of course, he was great.

1495
01:26:10,799 --> 01:26:12,901
We study him
at Moscow Conservatory,

1496
01:26:12,935 --> 01:26:17,005
but growing up, my favorite
is Jacqueline du Pré.

1497
01:26:17,039 --> 01:26:19,775
She made me want to play cello.

1498
01:26:19,808 --> 01:26:21,277
Which record was it?

1499
01:26:21,310 --> 01:26:23,812
Not record. YouTube.

1500
01:26:23,846 --> 01:26:25,848
Elgar Concerto.

1501
01:26:27,616 --> 01:26:28,917
Oh, of course.

1502
01:26:28,951 --> 01:26:31,654
With Barenboim conducting
the London Phil.

1503
01:26:31,687 --> 01:26:34,590
I don't know who was conducting.

1504
01:26:34,623 --> 01:26:37,326
But she did something to me.

1505
01:26:37,360 --> 01:26:39,194
That's when I decide
to learn piece

1506
01:26:39,228 --> 01:26:41,864
and play it
with youth orchestra.

1507
01:26:41,897 --> 01:26:43,766
Quite a challenge.
How old were you?

1508
01:26:43,799 --> 01:26:45,701
Thirteen.

1509
01:26:47,135 --> 01:26:48,737
Wow.

1510
01:26:48,771 --> 01:26:50,673
I'd love to hear it.

1511
01:26:50,706 --> 01:26:53,342
They make video.
I will text to you.

1512
01:26:55,478 --> 01:26:58,914
(ensemble playing Elgar's Cello
Concerto in E minor, Op. 85)

1513
01:27:21,770 --> 01:27:24,006
*

1514
01:27:39,855 --> 01:27:41,990
(knocking on door)

1515
01:27:49,932 --> 01:27:52,167
(knocking on door)

1516
01:27:54,169 --> 01:27:55,938
-(pounding on door)
-(music stops)

1517
01:28:14,390 --> 01:28:16,825
(quiet high-pitched tone
in distance)

1518
01:28:41,316 --> 01:28:43,552
(high-pitched tone continues)

1519
01:28:53,762 --> 01:28:55,998
(high-pitched tone stops)

1520
01:29:00,302 --> 01:29:02,337
(panting)

1521
01:29:10,446 --> 01:29:12,881
(orchestra playing
classical music)

1522
01:29:42,244 --> 01:29:44,480
(final note fades slowly)

1523
01:30:01,664 --> 01:30:03,365
Beautiful.

1524
01:30:06,735 --> 01:30:09,371
(speaking German)

1525
01:30:13,075 --> 01:30:16,111
Now, um, just before we break,

1526
01:30:16,144 --> 01:30:18,180
I know many of you are wondering

1527
01:30:18,213 --> 01:30:21,183
what the companion piece
will be.

1528
01:30:21,216 --> 01:30:23,619
And I have been
thinking quite a bit about it

1529
01:30:23,652 --> 01:30:25,588
and was wondering
if we could just take

1530
01:30:25,621 --> 01:30:29,224
an informal poll about
possibly pairing the Five

1531
01:30:29,257 --> 01:30:32,327
with Elgar's Cello Concerto.

1532
01:30:34,096 --> 01:30:37,099
(quiet murmuring)

1533
01:30:48,076 --> 01:30:50,312
(bows tapping)

1534
01:30:54,583 --> 01:30:57,352
(speaks German)

1535
01:30:58,220 --> 01:31:02,891
Oh, and, uh, given what
we've all been through,

1536
01:31:02,925 --> 01:31:04,627
what we're still going through,

1537
01:31:04,660 --> 01:31:09,197
and we're finally back
together as a family, I-I...

1538
01:31:10,398 --> 01:31:12,400
... I feel that
maybe the soloist

1539
01:31:12,434 --> 01:31:15,170
should come from
within our own ranks.

1540
01:31:15,203 --> 01:31:16,572
-(excited chatter)
-MAN: Yeah.

1541
01:31:16,605 --> 01:31:17,973
(bows tapping)

1542
01:31:18,006 --> 01:31:19,407
TÁR:
Good. Okay, good.

1543
01:31:19,441 --> 01:31:22,244
Just... Sorry. (chuckles)
One more question.

1544
01:31:22,277 --> 01:31:24,513
And this really is
just for you, Gosia.

1545
01:31:24,547 --> 01:31:26,148
I mean... (sighs)

1546
01:31:26,181 --> 01:31:28,884
... as a practical matter,
I mean, this would

1547
01:31:28,917 --> 01:31:30,886
normally fall to you.

1548
01:31:30,919 --> 01:31:33,589
But given how much is gonna be
asked of you with the Mahler,

1549
01:31:33,622 --> 01:31:35,724
I-I wondered if you'd be
at all bothered

1550
01:31:35,758 --> 01:31:38,326
if we were to hold auditions?

1551
01:31:47,169 --> 01:31:50,606
(chuckling):
Well, that's a bit unorthodox.

1552
01:31:53,508 --> 01:31:56,612
But, in theory,
I have no objection.

1553
01:31:56,645 --> 01:31:58,280
My only hesitation
will depend on

1554
01:31:58,313 --> 01:31:59,882
when these auditions
might take place.

1555
01:31:59,915 --> 01:32:01,349
I wouldn't want them in any way

1556
01:32:01,383 --> 01:32:02,585
to interfere with
our sectionals.

1557
01:32:02,618 --> 01:32:04,486
No, no, no.
That's a good point.

1558
01:32:04,519 --> 01:32:06,188
I mean, it is gonna
have to be a... (laughs)

1559
01:32:06,221 --> 01:32:07,756
It's gonna have to be a sprint.

1560
01:32:07,790 --> 01:32:09,357
Um...

1561
01:32:10,826 --> 01:32:12,595
How about Monday?

1562
01:32:16,632 --> 01:32:18,300
All right.

1563
01:32:21,403 --> 01:32:22,738
TÁR:
Okay, good.

1564
01:32:22,771 --> 01:32:26,008
Knut, would you assemble
a quorum for Monday?

1565
01:32:26,041 --> 01:32:27,442
(speaks quietly)

1566
01:32:31,814 --> 01:32:34,583
(quiet murmuring)

1567
01:32:40,923 --> 01:32:43,191
WOMAN:
Let me see what she says.

1568
01:32:43,225 --> 01:32:45,160
Okay, I got, I gotta go.

1569
01:32:46,261 --> 01:32:47,996
Britta, hi.

1570
01:32:48,030 --> 01:32:49,231
Lydia.

1571
01:32:49,264 --> 01:32:50,899
-Just caught the end.
-Ah!

1572
01:32:50,933 --> 01:32:53,001
What'd you think? How's it, uh,
how's it sounding?

1573
01:32:53,035 --> 01:32:55,303
Oh, it's fantastic.

1574
01:32:55,337 --> 01:32:57,439
I can't wait
until the live recording.

1575
01:32:57,472 --> 01:32:59,307
-Yes, well.
-(kissing)

1576
01:32:59,341 --> 01:33:01,844
I'll be happy when it's over.

1577
01:33:01,877 --> 01:33:03,646
It's always that way.

1578
01:33:03,679 --> 01:33:06,882
I know you're busy, and I don't
want to add to your load,

1579
01:33:06,915 --> 01:33:09,051
but...

1580
01:33:09,084 --> 01:33:11,253
Andris Davis called.

1581
01:33:11,286 --> 01:33:14,322
Look, he's upset
I'm rotating Sebastian.

1582
01:33:14,356 --> 01:33:15,891
No, no, no, no, no.

1583
01:33:15,924 --> 01:33:17,259
Something else.

1584
01:33:17,292 --> 01:33:18,661
But you will please
let Laura know

1585
01:33:18,694 --> 01:33:20,062
as soon as you have chosen
his replacement

1586
01:33:20,095 --> 01:33:21,263
so she can prepare
a press release.

1587
01:33:21,296 --> 01:33:22,831
Yeah, of course.

1588
01:33:22,865 --> 01:33:24,667
Uh, so what did he want?

1589
01:33:24,700 --> 01:33:26,869
To complain about
the punctuality of a driver

1590
01:33:26,902 --> 01:33:29,972
he seems to believe
the board supplies him with.

1591
01:33:30,005 --> 01:33:31,974
Do you know anything about this?

1592
01:33:32,007 --> 01:33:33,441
Yes.

1593
01:33:33,475 --> 01:33:36,478
No, it's just... it's just
something I pay for.

1594
01:33:36,511 --> 01:33:39,214
Then why does he believe
it's the board?

1595
01:33:39,247 --> 01:33:42,350
Because he needs
to believe that.

1596
01:33:42,384 --> 01:33:44,386
H-He needs to b...

1597
01:33:44,419 --> 01:33:46,755
needs to believe he hasn't
been forgotten, Britta.

1598
01:33:46,789 --> 01:33:49,692
Uh, the academy
has von Karajan's name on it,

1599
01:33:49,725 --> 01:33:52,127
and there are love shrines
to Abbado all over this place.

1600
01:33:52,160 --> 01:33:56,732
But the name of Davis, it's
essentially nowhere to be seen.

1601
01:33:56,765 --> 01:33:58,166
All right.

1602
01:33:58,200 --> 01:34:01,837
Then perhaps Francesca could
have a word with the driver.

1603
01:34:01,870 --> 01:34:04,106
Of course.

1604
01:34:04,139 --> 01:34:06,108
One other thing.

1605
01:34:06,141 --> 01:34:07,976
It's unpleasant.

1606
01:34:08,010 --> 01:34:09,344
Oh, is it?

1607
01:34:09,377 --> 01:34:11,446
Operational shortfall?

1608
01:34:11,479 --> 01:34:13,849
Must I take Mrs. Sewing
out to drinks again?

1609
01:34:13,882 --> 01:34:15,851
No, no, no, nothing to do
with the orchestra.

1610
01:34:15,884 --> 01:34:18,220
Do you remember
an Accordion Academy fellow

1611
01:34:18,253 --> 01:34:20,723
named Krista Taylor?

1612
01:34:23,892 --> 01:34:25,861
Yes. Why?

1613
01:34:25,894 --> 01:34:28,463
Apparently,
she committed suicide.

1614
01:34:28,496 --> 01:34:31,800
Oh, God. Poor thing.

1615
01:34:31,834 --> 01:34:33,869
Her parents mu...

1616
01:34:34,669 --> 01:34:37,472
Wait, sorry,
I'm... I'm confused, Britta.

1617
01:34:37,505 --> 01:34:39,607
Why, why were you put
in the position

1618
01:34:39,641 --> 01:34:40,976
to deliver this terrible news?

1619
01:34:41,009 --> 01:34:43,278
Why didn't Accordion
contact me directly?

1620
01:34:43,311 --> 01:34:45,280
It's delicate, Lydia.

1621
01:34:45,313 --> 01:34:46,882
Mr. Kaplan thought
it might be best

1622
01:34:46,915 --> 01:34:48,283
if you contacted a lawyer

1623
01:34:48,316 --> 01:34:50,853
before speaking with anyone
at Accordion.

1624
01:34:50,886 --> 01:34:54,256
Well, presumably, that anyone
includes Eliot himself.

1625
01:34:56,091 --> 01:34:59,627
I'm, I'm sorry, why-why
would I need to do that?

1626
01:34:59,661 --> 01:35:03,832
Apparently, some accusations
have been made.

1627
01:35:05,667 --> 01:35:07,669
Accusations?
What kind of accusations?

1628
01:35:07,702 --> 01:35:09,337
He didn't say.

1629
01:35:09,371 --> 01:35:11,706
But they were brought
to Accordion's counsel.

1630
01:35:11,740 --> 01:35:14,609
Mr. Kaplan said he's certain
nothing will come of it,

1631
01:35:14,642 --> 01:35:17,379
but one can't be too careful.

1632
01:35:24,486 --> 01:35:26,855
(sighs heavily)

1633
01:35:31,894 --> 01:35:33,528
(sniffs)

1634
01:35:35,931 --> 01:35:38,500
I'm sorry about the hour.
It's Lydia Tár calling.

1635
01:35:38,533 --> 01:35:41,703
I need to speak to Mr. Singer
immediately.

1636
01:35:41,736 --> 01:35:43,138
Yes.

1637
01:35:43,171 --> 01:35:44,940
Yes, it's urgent.

1638
01:36:09,131 --> 01:36:11,366
(low, quiet conversations)

1639
01:36:14,136 --> 01:36:15,971
Tired?

1640
01:36:19,241 --> 01:36:21,743
Sleep's elusive.

1641
01:36:22,544 --> 01:36:24,947
I was the same
before a recording date.

1642
01:36:26,882 --> 01:36:28,650
Lydia...

1643
01:36:28,683 --> 01:36:32,387
are-are you absolutely
certain about Sebastian?

1644
01:36:32,420 --> 01:36:34,656
TÁR:
Mm-hmm.

1645
01:36:34,689 --> 01:36:37,459
Who will you replace him with?

1646
01:36:37,492 --> 01:36:39,995
Possibly Andrew Crust.

1647
01:36:40,795 --> 01:36:44,232
He's been assisting
Otto Tausk at the VSO.

1648
01:36:44,266 --> 01:36:46,701
Not the girl?

1649
01:36:52,007 --> 01:36:54,042
(Tár sighs)

1650
01:36:55,310 --> 01:36:57,612
Andris...

1651
01:37:00,682 --> 01:37:03,618
... have you ever had an issue

1652
01:37:03,651 --> 01:37:06,188
with a, a student or colleague,

1653
01:37:06,221 --> 01:37:08,490
where that person may have
misinterpreted your intention?

1654
01:37:08,523 --> 01:37:10,058
Has someone been complaining
about me?

1655
01:37:10,092 --> 01:37:12,127
-No, no, no, of course not.
-Because at this point,

1656
01:37:12,160 --> 01:37:13,661
they've missed their chance.

1657
01:37:13,695 --> 01:37:15,864
-I'm out of the game.
-Yes, yes, I know, I know.

1658
01:37:15,898 --> 01:37:17,099
Course you are.

1659
01:37:17,132 --> 01:37:19,234
Thank God I was never pulled
from the podium

1660
01:37:19,267 --> 01:37:21,303
like Jimmy Levine.

1661
01:37:21,336 --> 01:37:24,940
Or-or hunted
like Charles Dutoit.

1662
01:37:24,973 --> 01:37:27,742
I take it you're asking
for a reason.

1663
01:37:27,775 --> 01:37:30,545
Well, there's just been
so much of this sort of thing

1664
01:37:30,578 --> 01:37:32,214
in the news lately.

1665
01:37:32,247 --> 01:37:35,783
Well, nowadays, to be accused
is the same as being guilty.

1666
01:37:36,584 --> 01:37:38,086
But I suppose
that was also the case

1667
01:37:38,120 --> 01:37:41,423
all those years ago
with Furtwängler.

1668
01:37:41,456 --> 01:37:44,526
A bit with Karajan, too.

1669
01:37:47,162 --> 01:37:49,864
Who was the better conductor?

1670
01:37:50,665 --> 01:37:53,068
I never played
under Furtwängler.

1671
01:37:53,101 --> 01:37:55,637
Yeah, when I first arrived here,
the older members

1672
01:37:55,670 --> 01:37:58,941
had, uh, hmm, hushed opinions.

1673
01:37:58,974 --> 01:38:02,344
At the same time, they wanted
to leave that era behind.

1674
01:38:02,377 --> 01:38:03,745
What, the war?

1675
01:38:03,778 --> 01:38:05,247
-No, postwar.
-Ah.

1676
01:38:05,280 --> 01:38:07,415
Denazification.

1677
01:38:07,449 --> 01:38:09,184
Someone pointed a finger at you,

1678
01:38:09,217 --> 01:38:11,319
process started all over again.

1679
01:38:11,353 --> 01:38:13,788
Furtwängler never joined
the Party.

1680
01:38:13,821 --> 01:38:15,390
Refused to give the salute

1681
01:38:15,423 --> 01:38:17,559
or to conduct the
"Horst-Wessel-Lied."

1682
01:38:17,592 --> 01:38:20,395
Or to sign his letters,
"Heil, Hitler."

1683
01:38:20,428 --> 01:38:23,431
Even those he wrote to Hitler.

1684
01:38:23,465 --> 01:38:27,936
But he was obliged
to be denazified.

1685
01:38:27,970 --> 01:38:30,939
Until then, he was semiretired,

1686
01:38:30,973 --> 01:38:33,475
playing corpses.

1687
01:38:34,276 --> 01:38:36,444
Playing corpses?

1688
01:38:36,478 --> 01:38:39,781
Secretly performing
in a graveyard.

1689
01:38:41,149 --> 01:38:43,618
You're not equating
sexual impropriety

1690
01:38:43,651 --> 01:38:45,887
with being an accused Nazi?

1691
01:38:46,721 --> 01:38:48,390
Either way, you had to be ready.

1692
01:38:48,423 --> 01:38:51,359
For years, I made sure
all the hangers in my closet

1693
01:38:51,393 --> 01:38:53,595
were facing the same direction.

1694
01:39:04,006 --> 01:39:07,042
How many are auditioning
on Monday?

1695
01:39:11,313 --> 01:39:12,847
No one.

1696
01:39:13,615 --> 01:39:15,450
No one?

1697
01:39:17,019 --> 01:39:19,487
Maybe Martin.

1698
01:39:19,521 --> 01:39:21,156
He's never gotten along
with Gosia.

1699
01:39:21,189 --> 01:39:23,958
He would love to sit downstage
for once.

1700
01:39:25,493 --> 01:39:27,962
Well...

1701
01:39:27,996 --> 01:39:30,465
he's still gonna
have to audition.

1702
01:39:32,267 --> 01:39:34,236
Of course.

1703
01:39:34,269 --> 01:39:36,504
Have to follow the rules.

1704
01:39:38,140 --> 01:39:40,808
TÁR: Aren't we being
a bit formal, Francesca?

1705
01:39:40,842 --> 01:39:43,478
From what I understand,
there's only one player, right?

1706
01:39:43,511 --> 01:39:46,214
FRANCESCA:
No, Maestro, there are two.

1707
01:39:47,782 --> 01:39:51,019
(cello and piano playing
dramatic classical music)

1708
01:40:09,171 --> 01:40:12,607
(cello playing Elgar's Cello
Concerto in E minor, Op. 85)

1709
01:40:41,669 --> 01:40:44,139
(cello holding final note)

1710
01:40:48,610 --> 01:40:50,612
SHARON:
Well, it's unanimous.

1711
01:40:50,645 --> 01:40:53,281
-Number two.
-TÁR: Mm-hmm.

1712
01:40:53,315 --> 01:40:54,716
And we have a problem.

1713
01:40:54,749 --> 01:40:56,017
She's not officially
been invited

1714
01:40:56,050 --> 01:40:58,186
to become a member
of the orchestra.

1715
01:40:59,387 --> 01:41:03,024
Well, she wouldn't need to be
to solo for us.

1716
01:41:03,057 --> 01:41:05,227
KNUT: I believe the criteria
of the audition

1717
01:41:05,260 --> 01:41:07,495
was all section members?

1718
01:41:07,529 --> 01:41:10,132
-(grunts) Then her audition
gets thrown out. -SHARON: No.

1719
01:41:10,165 --> 01:41:12,634
Francesca, please ask Martin
to come back in

1720
01:41:12,667 --> 01:41:14,736
so we can give him the news.

1721
01:41:14,769 --> 01:41:16,971
Wait. Gosia, let's talk.

1722
01:41:19,341 --> 01:41:21,676
Shit! (laughing)

1723
01:41:21,709 --> 01:41:23,077
(whooping loudly)

1724
01:41:23,111 --> 01:41:25,547
Yeah! (continues laughing
and whooping)

1725
01:41:26,914 --> 01:41:30,385
I'll confirm solo rehearsal
dates with her.

1726
01:41:30,418 --> 01:41:32,354
Thank you.

1727
01:41:32,387 --> 01:41:34,556
Have a seat.

1728
01:41:38,826 --> 01:41:40,862
(sighs):
I have made a decision

1729
01:41:40,895 --> 01:41:43,665
regarding Sebastian's
replacement.

1730
01:41:44,832 --> 01:41:48,336
And I want you to know
it wasn't an easy one.

1731
01:41:49,871 --> 01:41:54,342
Uh, this position brings with it
enormous responsibility,

1732
01:41:54,376 --> 01:41:57,545
-and my personal affection
for you aside... -(scoffs)

1733
01:41:57,579 --> 01:42:02,684
... I will have to go with
someone more, more experienced.

1734
01:42:17,765 --> 01:42:20,001
(quiet high-pitched tone)

1735
01:42:25,440 --> 01:42:27,074
(tone stops)

1736
01:42:42,857 --> 01:42:45,092
(playing simple melody)

1737
01:42:53,000 --> 01:42:55,237
(bell chiming in distance)

1738
01:42:59,307 --> 01:43:02,477
-(knocking on door)
-(plays note)

1739
01:43:02,510 --> 01:43:04,512
Oh, leave me alone.

1740
01:43:04,546 --> 01:43:06,914
I don't have your paper.

1741
01:43:07,715 --> 01:43:09,717
I've told you before, I...

1742
01:43:09,751 --> 01:43:11,953
Oh, I'm sorry. Please come in.

1743
01:43:16,691 --> 01:43:18,092
(sighs)

1744
01:43:18,125 --> 01:43:20,362
(playing gentle melody)

1745
01:43:57,799 --> 01:43:59,267
Good. Good.

1746
01:43:59,301 --> 01:44:02,136
I-I think the contrast is,
it's much better now.

1747
01:44:02,169 --> 01:44:03,871
-Don't you think?
-Hmm.

1748
01:44:03,905 --> 01:44:05,740
(sighs)
How do you take your coffee?

1749
01:44:05,773 --> 01:44:08,009
Black. Strong.

1750
01:44:09,677 --> 01:44:11,346
Is all right if I play?

1751
01:44:11,379 --> 01:44:14,115
Hmm? Oh, yes,
of course, of course.

1752
01:44:24,091 --> 01:44:26,328
(playing gentle melody)

1753
01:45:02,597 --> 01:45:04,999
That's as far as I've gotten.

1754
01:45:05,032 --> 01:45:07,034
